<HEADLINE> Thousands Flee Fresh Angola Conflict: UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people have fled fresh
fighting in Angola between government and rebel forces, said the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 people had fled to the neighboring Democratic
Republic of the Congo, formerly Zaire, in the past week and had
taken shelter in the southeastern Kisenge area where there were
now 22,000 refugees, said UNHCR spokesman Kris Janowski.
</P>
<P>
"There is a continuing outflow of people as a result of
fighting between UNITA (National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola) and government forces," Janowski said at a press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government and the opposition UNITA fought a
20-year civil war in the southern African country before a 1994
peace agreement which has since failed. The conflict has left an
estimated 150,000 Angolans internally-displaced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
