<HEADLINE> China Reiterates Its Positions on So-called "Taiwan's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan has been an
inalienable part of China since ancient times, Qin Huasun, Chinese
Ambassador to the United Nations, stressed here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. Secretary-General, Qin said the 1943
Cairo Declaration and the 1945 Potsdam Proclamation once again
reaffirmed China's sovereignty over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qin said to date, 162 countries have established
diplomatic relations with China, and they all recognize that there
is but one China in the world, that the Government of the People's
Republic of China is the sole legal Government representing China
in its entirety and that Taiwan is an inalienable part of China.
</P>
<P>
Qin said over the past 50 years or so since the founding of the
People's Republic of China, great changes have taken place both in
the world situation and in China, including Taiwan, in the social,
economic, political and other aspects.
</P>
<P>
Qin noted that however, no such change can alter the fact that
Taiwan is a province of China and that China exercises sovereignty
over Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
