<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Israel Defies U.N. Statement On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel Tuesday showed defiance
to a United Nations Security Council presidential statement which
urged it to abandon its controversial plan to expand Jerusalem,
while the Palestinians welcomed it.
</P>
<P>
"We regrets the Presidential Statement adopted yesterday by
the United Nations Security Council," the Israeli Foreign Ministry
said. "Israel has already clarified that the Cabinet decision of
June 21, 1998 does not contradict the agreements between Israel
and the Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
However, the Palestinian National Authority Cabinet Secretary
Ahmad Abdel Rahman told the Voice of Palestine radio that the
Security Council presidential statement is a moral and political
condemnation to the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council issued the presidential statement later
Monday, deeming the Israeli plan a "serious and damaging
development" which will jeopardize the Israeli-Palestinian talks
on the final status of the city. It called on Israel not to
proceed with it.
</P>
<P>
Israel has come under fire from the international community by
approving the controversial plan last month to expand Jerusalem to
include Jewish settlements in the West Bank. Palestinians, who
want Jerusalem as capital of their future state, said this will
lead to annexation of occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
One of the latest waves of criticism came from a three-way
summit in Cairo early this month held by Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak, Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat and
Jordan's King Hussein. The three leaders warned Israel against
"play fire" on the Jerusalem issue and asserted their "absolute
rejection" of the expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council presidential statement, however, was a
result of compromise in the 15-member council, which began debate
on the plan early this month. The United States and Britain have
led a diplomatic drive to prevent the Security Council from voting
on a resolution condemning Israel's plan as pressed for by Arab
states, saying such a resolution would make it more difficult to
get the stalled peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
A presidential statement requires the agreement of every
member of the council, but it does not carry the same weight as a
vote, since it is non-binding.
</P>
<P>
Rahman expressed the hope that the Security Council's position
will oblige Israel to halt settlements and expansion policy which
violates the signed agreements and endangers the entire peace
process.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the U.N. statement and its condemnation lacks
the mechanism of forcing Israel to drop its Jerusalem expansion
scheme.
</P>
<P>
In its reaction, the Israeli Foreign Ministry reiterated that
the plan "is municipal in nature," saying that it "is intended to
extend Jerusalem's municipal jurisdiction only to areas west of
the city."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council presidential statement "ignores these
facts," it argued.
</P>
<P>
"Israel will continue to work for the development and
prosperity of Jerusalem, for the benefit of all its inhabitants,"
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo Accords, the fate of Jerusalem can only be
determined in the permanent peace talks and before that, no side
should take unilateral actions to change its status, demographic
composition or character. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
