<HEADLINE> India Rules out Plebiscite in Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian Defense Minister George
Fernandes Tuesday turned down Pakistan's demand for a plebiscite
in Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen here, Fernandes argued that it was too late
to discuss the question of a plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistan High Commissioner to India Ashraf Jehangir
Qazi said in a newspaper interview here that Jammu and Kashmir is
an indivisible state which is neither part of India nor Pakistan.
He reiterated Pakistan's stand to carry out the 1948 U.N.
Resolution on Kashmir which referred to a plebiscite on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' prime ministers, Nawaz Sharif and Atal
Behari Vajpayee, are scheduled to meet on the fringes of a
three-day summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) to be held in Colombo on July 29-31.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled meeting comes in the aftermath of the nuclear
explosions by the two countries in May this year. The nuclear
tests have further aggravated the relations between the two
arch-rivals in South Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
