<HEADLINE> Three Young Arson Victims laid to Rest in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Three young brothers killed in an
arson attack on their home in Ballymoney, Northern Ireland, were
laid to rest in a single, simple grave on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
BBC reports said the funeral was held at the Roman Catholic
Church of Our Lady in Ballymoney, but mourners came from both
Protestant and Catholic communities who packed the church to bid
farewell to the three young boys from 11 to nine -- Richard, Mark
and Jason Quinn.
</P>
<P>
The children's grief-stricken mother, Christine, sat
expressionless in front of the small white coffins with her
surviving son Lee, 12.
</P>
<P>
Although Christine is a Catholic, she sent her sons to a
Protestant school and has a Protestant partner.
</P>
<P>
In his sermon Father Peter Forde told the congregation that the
deaths of the three boys had provoked a "great outpouring of
sorrow and sympathy" from all sides of the political and religious
divide across Northern Ireland and the world.
</P>
<P>
Two men were arrested on Monday by police investigating the
arson attack and were questioned over the brutal murder case.
</P>
<P>
The boys' deaths in their home followed a week of sporadic
clashes in the town of Portadown between security forces and
Protestant Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
The Orangemen are continuing to protest at Drumcree against a
ban on their march along a route which includes a Catholic
neighborhood.  
</P>
</TEXT>
