<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Security Council on the Side of the Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Tuesday described a presidential statement issued by the United
Nations Security Council criticizing Israel's Jerusalem expansion
as a rare support for "the side of the right."
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, the Security Council supports the side of
the right. The U.S. delegate to the Council did the same until a
strong-worded statement was passed," said Mubarak after the
graduation ceremony of the 49th Naval cadet batch held in the
Mediterranean city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council approved Monday night a presidential
statement that calls Israel's June 21 decision "a serious and
damaging development." It also calls on Israel not to proceed with
the expansion of Jerusalem's boundaries.
</P>
<P>
Hailing the statement, Mubarak said that it was issued at a
time "Israel is defying the world community while nobody even
utters one word."
</P>
<P>
He expressed deep regret over the impasse in the Mideast peace
march over the past 16 months, and held Israel responsible for
sabotaging the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Israel should be aware of the reflections of the current grave
situation on the whole region and on its people," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council statement also calls on the parties
directly concerned with the Mideast peace to negotiate and not to
change the features of the occupied Palestinian territories,
including Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak noted that there are still "some people who take more
than their rights, while others lose their own rights with nobody
helping them retrieve their rights," referring to Israel and the
Palestinians respectively.
</P>
<P>
He expressed apprehensions that this state of affairs will
easily damage the credibility of the world major powers and the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"This could also lead to an imbalance worldwide, coupled with a
state of confusion prevailing, a matter which is extremely
dangerous for mankind in general," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council statement is a compromise of its 15
members. The Arab countries had demanded a resolution condemning
Israel, but the U.S. and Britain launched a diplomatic drive to
prevent from happening.
</P>
<P>
The Arab-sponsored draft resolution was softened to a
presidential statement after repeated U.S. objections and intense
negotiations between Washington and Arab capitals.
</P>
<P>
Such a statement does not carry the weight of international law
that a resolution does and is non-binding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
