<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Reports Substantial Increase in Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, the capital of China,
recorded a 12.8 percent increase in foreign trade during the first
six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by Beijing Customs show that the city's
Jan-June import and export volume hit 2.91 billion US dollars, up
12.8 percent, with its export volume reaching 1.37 billion US
dollars, 22.6 percent more than the figure for the same 1997
period, and with its imports climbing by 5.3 percent to reach 1.54
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Southeast Asian financial crisis has affected Beijing's
export to Southeast Asian nations, which has gone down by 24
percent in the first half of the year as compared with the same
period of last year, and its export to Japan and the Republic of
Korea, which has decreased.
</P>
<P>
However, Beijing's exports to the Untied States grew by 19
percent in the period, to Europe by 54 percent and to Africa by
nearly 300 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
