<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Police Shoot Dead Two Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Two militants wanted in a slew of
fatal terrorist attacks since 1993 were killed Tuesday during an
hour-long gun battle with the police in southern Egypt, the Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the Interior Ministry, the
shoot-out in Abu Qirqas, Minya, about 220 kilometers south of
Cairo, left the two assailants killed and a police conscript
wounded. A third attacker managed to escape and is being pursued
by the police.
</P>
<P>
The three had planned to attack a police patrol in the southern
province, a hotbed of extremist violence. Acting upon a tip-off,
security forces laid siege at their hideout.
</P>
<P>
Police found with the two terrorists two automatic rifles and
two bags containing clothes, food and some documents.
</P>
<P>
The ministry identified them as Yehia Ali Sediq, and Hamza
Abdel Hamid Abdul Moeez, belonging to the military wing of the
outlawed Gamaa Islamia, or the Islamic Group, which is blamed for
most of the violence since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Sediq had been involved since 1993 in 21 terror acts which left
15 people killed and eight others and 11 policemen wounded, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Abdul Moeez was a leading fugitive terrorist
who had been involved in 20 acts of terror since 1993 which killed
24 civilians and seven policemen, and injured nine civilians and
five policemen.
</P>
<P>
The clash was the first in Egypt since March when security
forces killed a suspected Muslim militant in the south.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,200 people have been killed in the past six years
since a violent insurgence was launched by Islamic militants
seeking to overthrow Egypt's secular government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
