<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Import 65,000 Tons of Wheat from U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe signed a 10-million-U.S.
Dollar loan agreement Tuesday with the United State to import
65,000 tons of wheat from the U.S. during the
September-to-December period of this year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed here by U.S. Ambassador to Zimbabwe
Tom MacDonald and Zimbabwe's Deputy Finance Minister Misheck
Chinamasa.
</P>
<P>
"This is a concessionary loan agreement which has very
favourable terms to the Zimbabwean government," said MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
"It provides reasonable terms of repayment which will start
five years after the last delivery of wheat. The repayments will
be at an interest rate of between three and four percent," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe imports a total of 100,000 tons of wheat each year to
meet domestic needs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
