<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Welcomes Security Council Statement on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Tuesday
welcomed the United Nations Security Council statement calling on
Israel not to proceed with its decision to expand Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The statement marks a strong start to urge Israel to stop all
arbitrary and expansionist measures in Jerusalem, and implement
the Oslo accord and all Security Council resolutions of relevance
to the peace process," said Saeed Kamal, the AL assistant
secretary-general for Palestine affairs.
</P>
<P>
The presidential statement passed by the 15-member Security
Council Monday night deemed the Israeli plan on broaden Jerusalem,
the most sensitive issue in the peace process, a "serious and
damaging development."
</P>
<P>
It also calls on the parties directly concerned with the
Mideast to negotiate and not to change the features of the
occupied Palestinian territories, including Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to the Middle East News Agency, Kamal slammed the
Israeli rejection of the Security Council's statement, describing
the reaction as "a dangerous precedent."
</P>
<P>
He said this should prompt the Security Council into holding an
emergency meeting to take a substitute resolution for the
statement issued Monday night to "lend it a legal status."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain had tried to prevent the Security Council
from voting on an Arab-sponsored resolution condemning Israel, and
the 15 council members finally compromised on a watered-down
presidential statement which is non-binding and does not carry the
same weight as a resolution.
</P>
<P>
Kamal also demanded an international committee to be set up to
be permanently posted to Jerusalem to monitor Israel's illegal
measures and compile a report to be referred to the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League is closely watching the developments in the
occupied territories as well as the whole peace process, he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel has come under under fire from the international
community by approving the controversial plan last month to
extend Jerusalem's boundaries to include Jewish settlements in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
It was regard as another Israeli attempt to breach the Oslo
accord, under which the fate of the city can only be determined in
the permanent peace talks and no side should take unilateral
actions to change its status, demographic composition or character
in advance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
