<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Chinese Taipei Bowlers Dominate Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Taipei's Kao Hai Yuan
and his top-seeded female teammate Ku Hui Chin won the men's and
women's title at the Hong Kong Bowling Masters Cup which closed
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day Hong Kong Masters Cup is the third stop of this
year's five-leg Asian Bowling Tour.
</P>
<P>
Kao, 45, winner of the Masters event at last year's Asian
Interport Championships, was the men's all-events runner-up at the
15th Far East championships held here earlier this month. Kao
beat his teammate and top seed Wang Tien Fu, men's singles
champion at the Far East championships, 214-211 at the
semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
In the championship final, Kao outscored his teammate and
second-seeded Hsieh Fu Tai, who beat Singapore's Jack Wong 243-222
to qualify for the final, 246-216. Hsieh is the Masters champion
at the Far East tournament.
</P>
<P>
Kao scored six consecutive strikes in the final to collect a
total of 246 points, 30 more than Hsieh for the title.
</P>
<P>
Ku of the women's group, a university student with playing
experience of four years, won the trios and five-player titles at
the Far East championships here.
</P>
<P>
Ku, 24, who beat teammate and winner of four gold medals at the
Far East championships Tseng Su Fen 195-186 in the semi-final
earlier in the day, went on to win the title with a 192-164 win
over Karen Lorenzana of hosts Hong Kong, China. Lorenzana, third
placer in the women's doubles at the Far East tournament, won over
Singapore's third-seeded Jesmine Ho, silver-medalist at the 1995
World Cup, in the semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
With three out of the five legs of the Asian Tour completed,
two are remaining: the Singapore Masters Cup on August 17-18 and
the Thailand Masters Cup on September 7-8 in Bangkok.
Participating bowlers won ranking points and prize money from the
series.
</P>
<P>
The top 16 men's and women's bowlers from the Tour ranking list
will enter the Grand Slam Finals slated for January 16-17 in
Taipei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
