<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Calls for Unity among Zimbabweans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Tuesday called on the Zimbabwean people to unite to surmount
economic difficulty the country is facing.
</P>
<P>
Opening the fourth session of the fourth parliament of
Zimbabwe, Mugabe said "The government has noted with dismay that
our urban and rural folk are suffering."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's new economic reform program which has begun
recently sought the urgent restoration of macro-economic
stability in order to stimulate growth, greater investment
activity, employment creation and the equitable distribution of
incomes across various sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The tasks ahead of us require all of us commitment, energy
and dedication. Equally importantly, they require an unshakeable
unity of purpose and action," he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the constitution issue, Mugabe hoped that this parliament
would be able to begin in earnest during this session to debate
this matter thoroughly so that the final agreed constitution will
truly reflect the wishes of the people.
</P>
<P>
Referring to land reform, the president said his government,
in consultation with the European Union and other donors, would
convene a land donor conference in Harare in September to
mobilize resources in support of the land policy program already
underway.
</P>
<P>
"While we welcome the financial and material support from the
donor community, we should always primarily rely on the strength
and resourcefulness of our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, said Mugabe, is making efforts to promote African
sub-regional and continental integration in pursuit of goals of
the Organization of African Unity and groupings such as the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) and the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) to which it
belonged.
</P>
<P>
"Similarly, in pursuit of our vital interest we remain active
on such fora as the United Nations, the Non-Aligned Movement and
the Commonwealth," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
