<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Delivery of Russian Missiles in August Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides
said Tuesday the Russian-made S-300 air defense system would not
be delivered to Cyprus by August, confirming a reported
postponement.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a press conference at the end of his
four-day visit to Moscow, where he held talks with his Russian
counterpart Boris Yeltsin and Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
the Cyprus News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Clerides told reporters that "the S-300s would not reach
Cyprus in August. A part of the system was scheduled to be
obtained in August, but Cyprus decided that the system should be
delivered as a whole, and the decision was conveyed to Russia."
</P>
<P>
Asked if there is any chance to cancel the deployment of the
system, he said his country's basic objective for a Cyprus
settlement would be a demilitarization agreement.
</P>
<P>
The east Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974 into
Greek Cypriot dominated south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north, and efforts to find a peaceful settlement has so for made
little progress.
</P>
<P>
"We proposed to the Turkish side the immediate start of talks
on demilitarization, and if an agreement was reached, a gradual
reduction of armed forces and armaments from both sides would
begin, followed by a timetable for the withdrawal of foreign
troops," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said "if this point was reached before the date of the
S-300's arrival, we would not obtain the missiles, but we would
pay the manufacturers."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government clinched a 425-million-U.S.-dollar deal
with Russians early last year to buy the surface-to-air missiles
with a range of 150 kilometers. This angered Turkish Cypriots and
their ally Turkey, who regarded the system as a threat to their
security.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that during the talks in the Kremlin, he
reiterated "our positions and insistence on a peaceful Cyprus
solution, using the U.N. Secretary-General's good offices
mission."
</P>
<P>
He underlined the need for the withdrawal of all foreign troops
from the island and the deployment of an international force
under the U.N. that would monitor the pullout, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the desire to buy "certain types of arms from
Russia," in addition to "various types of armored vehicles."
</P>
<P>
Russia supported Clerides' proposal for demilitarization of the
island as a precondition for cancellation of the missile deal.
</P>
<P>
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island in 1974 in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
It has kept a 40,000-strong force in northern Cyprus controlled
by the Turkish Cypriots, who declared in 1983 a breakaway state,
which was recognized by no other country than Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
