<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Highest Court Gives Green Light to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Germany's highest court Tuesday gave
the green light to the introduction of a German language reform
from August 1 this year after years of controversies.
</P>
<P>
In a much-awaited ruling on Tuesday, the German Federal
Constitutional Court also turned down a complaint by a German
couple who claimed that their basic parental rights to guide their
children's education were violated by the introduction of the new
language rules.
</P>
<P>
The German language reform was agreed to in July 1996 by
government ministers of the three German-speaking countries:
Austria, Germany and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
The changes include shortening lengthy compound nouns,
introducing more consistent spellings to avoid numerous exceptions
and cutting the number of the correct-writing rules from 212 to
112.
</P>
<P>
Officials say that the reform, the first comprehensive one
since 1901, is meant to make the written German language more
logical and easier to learn.
</P>
<P>
However, many academics, authors and parents, who like the old
way of writing, oppose the reform, and launched a number of legal
challenges to try to stop it.
</P>
<P>
Citizen groups in the northern German state of
Scheswig-Holstein have succeeded in forcing a referendum on
whether or not to implement the reform in the state.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting arguments that the reform would create confusions,
the German constitutional court said that the new rules would only
affect about 0.5 percent of German vocabulary and therefore would
not make German less comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
With the court ruling, it would be obligatory for schools
across Germany to adopt the new language rules from August 1 this
year. However, during a transitional period until 2005, the old
way of writing would still be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
The German Interior Ministry meanwhile said that it had still
to examine the court ruling before setting a deadline for
government offices and institutions to follow the new language
rules.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Agrees to Cut Wage Ahead of Teachers' Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
is to cut half of his wage as the nation's economy is facing a
tough time, the Kenyan government announced Tuesday, one day
before the planned country-wide teachers' pay strike.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the ongoing economic difficulties facing the
country, His Excellency the President has agreed to forfeit 50
percent of his salary," said Fares Kuindwa, the head of the
public service, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He said that cabinet ministers have also accepted a 30 percent
salary reduction but the move will not affect assistant ministers
and allowances will be excluded from the cut.
</P>
<P>
However, details of their wages are not available.
</P>
<P>
In another statement also issued on Tuesday, Moi said he will
name a commission to solve the dispute over civil servants'
salaries and allowances.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy is in a recession with real gross domestic
product shrinking in each of the first three months of 1998, and
high interest rates strangling private investment.
</P>
<P>
The 260,000-strong Kenya National Union of Teachers warned
Monday that it will launch a strike Wednesday unless the
government withdraws a bill on curbing the increments of teachers
salaries.
</P>
<P>
The union demanded the government implement their agreement
reached last year before Moi won his fifth term in the country's
second multi-party poll, to give teachers a 150-200 percent pay
rise over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
When announcing the 1998/99 budget on June 11, Finance
Minister Simeon Nyachae said the government just cannot afford to
implement the deal, asking the pay hike to be renegotiated and
new teachers recruitment to be frozen.
</P>
<P>
The increment on teachers salaries, if implemented in 1998,
will reportedly take up 30 percent of the total government
revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
