<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-14 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Costa Rican President: U.S. Soft on Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Former Costa Rican President Oscar
Arias here Tuesday blamed Washington for adopting a soft stand
over the Israeli government, which in effect contributes to the
stalemate in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. government did not put enough pressure on the
Israeli government to force it to change its intransigence
towards implementing the Oslo accords," said Arias in a statement
for Jordan's official news agency Petra.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government should have exerted more pressure on the
Israeli government to force it to implement the agreements already
signed with the Palestinians, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. should also have tried to make both sides resolve
their differences through peaceful dialog, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Dialog is the only means to solve outstanding issues and all
the concerned parties could reach comprehensive, just and
permanent peace that puts an end to the conflicts in the region,
through (such) dialog," Arais added in his statement.
</P>
<P>
Arias is in Jordan to attend a program organized by the United
Nations International Leadership Academy in Amman. He delivered a
lecture during the Tuesday session of the program.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been stalemated
for some 16 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
