<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rubin Backs South African Economic Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin Tuesday commended South African
government's macro-economic strategy of growth, employment and
redistribution as being on the right track.
</P>
<P>
In an address at Vista University in Soweto, Johannesburg,
Rubin said South Africa had followed sound fiscal and monetary
policies since the present government took power in 1994,
according to the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Rubin, in South Africa on the second leg of a five-nation
African visit, declined to comment on whether the Rand was
undervalued at its current levels after the speculative assault
on the currency over past weeks.
</P>
<P>
He urged South Africa to continue with its program of
integration into the global economy, despite the recent pressure
on the Rand.
</P>
<P>
"Emerging markets from around the globe have benefited
enormously from global integration, even taking into account the
recent crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
It had to be remembered that many Asian nations, while having
underlying problems which eventually led to the crisis, had
experienced between 20 and 30 years of high growth and reaped
enormous benefits.
</P>
<P>
"I believe Asian nations will get back on the path of solid
growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said economic progress would also entail finding ways to
make labor markets more flexible while protecting workers'
interests.
</P>
<P>
"Productivity growth is the only path over time to
competitiveness in the global economy, lower unemployment and
higher standards of living," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said he believed privatization was the most obvious and
immediate way South Africa could attract foreign investment, but
he believed an array of investment would flow in over time.
</P>
<P>
He repeated assurances that the U.S. would open its market to
African countries undertaking economic reform.
</P>
<P>
"With South Africa we can even envision the day when it will
be mutually advantageous to conclude a free trade agreement
together," he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is now engaged in talks for a free trade
agreement with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Asked for comment on the resignation of Ryutaro Hashimoto as
Japan's prime minister, Rubin said Hashimoto's successor must
deal with the country's troubled economy immediately for the sake
of world economy.
</P>
<P>
"Our view is that whoever may be in the government, it is
absolutely imperative for Japan and the rest of the world that
Japan move expeditiously on dealing with its bank problems and
more generally on issues of its economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the state of the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), Rubin said its historically low level of funding created a
risk of renewed financial instability. For this reason the U.S.
was pushing for IMF funding to be increased, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official is scheduled to meet South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki, Finance Minister Trevor Manuel and Reserve
Bank Governor Chris Stals later Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Rubin, who has visited Cote d'Ivoire, will proceed to Namibia,
Mozambique and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The aim of Rubin's African tour is to continue publicizing
Washington's new trade-for-aid African policy after U.S.
President Bill Clinton's historic Africa visit in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
