<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secret Autopsy Rules Out Poisoning of Abacha: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former head of state
General Sani Abacha died of natural causes, according to the
tissue and blood samples taken from him shortly before he was
buried on June 8, This Day newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abacha was announced died of heart attacked by the government
and was buried according to Muslim tradition with no postmortem
reported.
</P>
<P>
But This Day quoted sources conversant with the last moments
of late Abacha as saying that presidential doctors took some
blood, urine and tissue samples minutes after his death and flew
immediately to Germany for secret postmortem.
</P>
<P>
The result ruled out poisoning and foul play, the report said,
adding that there was no finding of Viagra (a new male potency
drug) used by the late leader as speculated by the United
States-based Newsweek magazine.
</P>
<P>
It has been widely spread that Abacha was in the company of
two ladies shortly before he died in the early hours of June 8.
</P>
<P>
The sudden death of Abacha has brought about a number of
changes in the most populous African country, which may finally
lead to a genuine transition from military to civil rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
