<HEADLINE> Romanian President leaves for Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu left here on Tuesday afternoon for a 7-day official
visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian President is accompanied by Defense Minister
Victor Babiuc, Foreign Minister Andrei Plesu, Finance Minister
Daniel Daianu, Privatization Minister Sorin Dimitriu, Transport
Minister Traian Basescu, Minister of Research and Technology Horia
Ene, presidential aides Zoe Petre and Dorin Marian.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu will meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton in
the Oval Office and will address the joint Houses of the Congress.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Romania and the U.S. have improved after
1989. The U.S. administration in 1990 included Romania in the work
programs of the Group 24. In 1993 the U.S. offered Romania the
most favored nation's status, and in 1996 the Chamber of
Representatives of the U.S. Congress endorsed a bill granting
Romania the most favored nation's status on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
The United States ranks among the first top foreign investors
in Romania, with 2000 American companies conducting businesses in
the east-European country.  
</P>
