<HEADLINE> Lebanon Calls for Release of Prisoners in Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Tuesday launched a
nationwide sit-in protest on the Prisoner Day to call for a
release of all Lebanese detainees held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
The country's non-governmental Follow-up Committee for
Supporting Lebanese Prisoners in Israeli Jails organized a sit-in
protest in front of the headquarters of the United Nations in
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Scores of Lebanese parliament members, university professors,
lawyers and prisoners recently freed from Israeli jails took part
in the protest.
</P>
<P>
They called on the U.N. and other international organizations
to pressure Israel to release all Lebanese detainees.
</P>
<P>
"Destroy Khiam Prison and release all Prisoners in Israeli
jails," they shouted.
</P>
<P>
The Khiam prison, established by Israeli forces in south
Lebanon, is used to hold those who fought against Israeli
occupation and those who refused to collaborate with the
pro-Israeli militia South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
Some 125 Lebanese are currently held in this prison and other
42 are in Israeli prisons.
</P>
<P>
Similar protests were also held in Lebanon's other important
cities like the biggest southern city Sidon, another big southern
city of Tyre and the central town of Nabatieh which faces the
Israeli occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Lebanese Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz met
with a delegation of released prisoners and their supporters.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the government will make every effort to help
seek the release of all Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Israel released 60 Lebanese prisoners and returned
bodies of 40 Lebanese guerrillas in exchange for the remains of an
Israeli soldier killed in south Lebanon last year.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon with a claimed aim to protect its north from
Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
