<HEADLINE> Ex-U.N. Chief Slams Foreign Meddling in Egypt's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The former Secretary General of the
United Nations Boutros Boutros-Ghali Tuesday warned against
"dangerous foreign bids" to drive a wedge between Egypt's Muslim
majority and Coptic Christians on pretext of human rights.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian people must unite to face these attempts, and any
problem, if any, should be handled at home," Ghali, who is chief
of La Francophonie, said in an interview with Egypt's Middle East
News Agency from Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Ghali, who is an Egyptian Christian, said that Muslims and
Copts are treated on an equal footing in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on some countries' exploitation of human
rights principles to interfere in others' internal affairs, Ghali
expressed sorrow that some principles are serving as
justifications for such attempts.
</P>
<P>
"Encountering this requires mobilizing public opinion and
enhancing the role of the United Nations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Some Coptic expatriates in the United States have been accusing
the Egyptian government of persecuting the minority Copts, Egypt's
aboriginals who traditionally live in the south. Cairo squarely
denies the charge.
</P>
<P>
But Copts, along with the police and foreign tourists, have
been a prime target of terrorist attacks staged by Muslim
militants since 1992. Muslims account for nearly 90 percent of the
population and Copts around 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
On a possible role by La Francophonie in the Middle East peace
process, Ghali said the organization, which groups 52
French-speaking countries whose majority are from Africa, was
still in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
"Besides, we have to avoid having many brokers," he said,
citing the role of the U.S. as the key sponsor of the Middle East
peace drive.
</P>
<P>
But still, La Francophonie can help in educating world public
opinion about the importance of grappling with the crisis
experienced by the Mideast peace process, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ghali was selected last November to steer the helm of La
Francophonie. Egypt, whose official language is Arabic, is a
member of the forum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
