<HEADLINE> Tanzanian, Burundi FMs Meet as Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) - Tanzanian Foreign Minister
Jakaya Kikwete has praised the commitment by the Burundi
government to join the oppositions in the second round of peace
talks due on July 20 in Arusha, northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting here Monday with his Burundi counterpart,
Severin Ntahomvukiye, Kikwete asserted that nothing but dialogs
can bring peace to the war-torn Burundi, said an official from
the foreign ministry Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete was quoted as saying that the Bujumbura's involvement
in the peace talks, which opened its first round in Arusha last
month under the facilitator Julius Nyerere, founding president of
Tanzania, was a "very encouraging signal."
</P>
<P>
Ntahomvukiye was accompanied by the Burundi Minister for Peace
and Reconciliation, Ambroise Niyonsaba, and the Executive
Secretary of opposition FRODEBU party, Dometien Ndahiyeze.
</P>
<P>
Concluding their meeting in Kikwete's office, the ministers
left together for Arusha in the afternoon to join Tanzanian
President Benjemin Mkapa, who is on a tour in the region.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
bloody conflicts between the ethnic Hutu majority and the ruling
Tutsi minority since the assassination of Melchior Ndadaye, the
first president elected under a multiparty system in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
