<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The slowdown in Israel's real estate sector
continued in the first half this year, with all activities,
including building starts, apartment sales and mortgages, dropping
compared with the same period in 1997, according to a Housing
Ministry report available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sales of new and second-hand apartments were down 8 percent
compared with the same period last year and the number of building
starts declined 26 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the slowdown, the number of mortgages taken by
those eligible for Housing Ministry assistance were down 19
percent in the January-May period.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Industry and Trade Ministry is to
launch its price-labeling information campaign next week under the
slogan of "consumer power," the Jerusalem Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Customers will be encouraged to ask stores to affix prices on
products as a condition for purchasing them and phone numbers will
be provided for them to register complaints with the ministry, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Investment Bank said it collected net
profits of 121.3 million riyals (32.3 million U.S. dollars) in the
first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
This was compared with 80.2 million riyals (about 21.4 million
dollars) in the same period last year, an increase of 51 percent,
the London-based Al Hayat newspaper reported Tuesday. 
</P>
