<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-capacity Memory Chip Due in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Early next year, Japan's
Hitachi Semiconductor plans to begin offering chip technology that
would allow a personal computer's main memory to store as much as
one gigabyte of data, according to CNET News today.
</P>
<P>
1GB memory module would be about 30 times the size of today's
PC standard. With such capacity, future PCs will be capable of
handling such task as the most realistic 3D graphics and
full-motion video applications. High-capacity memory chips will
also be necessary for next-generation operating systems.
</P>
<P>
Hitachi said that it has assembled its 1GB memory module from
36 256-megabit dynamic random access memory (DRAM) chips. By
comparison, most PCs come with 32MB of memory, using 16-megabit
chips.
</P>
<P>
DRAM technology is used for main memory in all PCs today. As
recently as last year, new notebook PCs came with hard drives
about the same size as the Hitachi memory chip.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the new memory module will be targeted for use in
high-performance workstations and servers, Hitachi said. The chips
are slated for volume production in the first quarter of 1999.
Everyday PCs will not see the technology for a while, as Hitachi
will set the initial prices at over 6,000 U.S. dollars early next
year.
</P>
<P>
Japanese and Korean memory makers are eager to advance memory
capacity, hoping to charge premium prices on advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
But in the United States, there has been talk of overinvestment
and overcapacity in memory manufacturing. The semiconductor
business has been experiencing lower demand, sinking prices and
poor earnings. Some Silicon Valley semiconductor companies and
related business have been scaling back their spending and hiring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
