<HEADLINE> Israeli Defiance to U.N. Statement Warned Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Palestine's permanent delegate to
the Cairo-based Arab League Mohamed Sobeih Tuesday voiced worries
that Israel would ignore a United Nations Security Council
statement calling it to rescind its plan to expand Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"We hoped this statement would have taken the shape of a
resolution because we know that the Israeli leadership would
deride this statement as it has done to the U.S., Arab and
international position," Sobeih told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Israel has come under under fire from the international
community by approving the controversial plan last month to extend
Jerusalem's boundaries to include Jewish settlements in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council issued the presidential statement late
Monday, deeming the Israeli plan a "serious and damaging
development" in the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on Israel not to act on its June 21
decision and "not to take any other steps which would prejudice
the outcome of the permanent status negotiations" with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem, a holy city claimed both by Israel and the
Palestinians, is the most sensitive issue in the peace process.
Under the Oslo accord, its fate can only be determined in
final-status talks and no side should take any unilateral action
before that.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain had tried to prevent the Security Council
from voting on an Arab-sponsored resolution condemning Israel, and
the 15 council members finally compromised on a watered-down
presidential statement which is non-binding and does not carry the
same weight as a resolution.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official, while admitting that the statement
included "many positive elements," maintained that Israel would
construe the absence of a resolution as "a green light to wage
more infringement and expansion."
</P>
<P>
Israel has shown defiance to the U.N. statement, expressing
"regret" to its adoption and vowing to "continue to work for the
development and prosperity of Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official also sounded pessimistic over the
outcome of direct negotiations with the Israelis expected to
start next week.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has agreed to send its chief
negotiator Abu Mazen to meet with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai in response to a call by U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked for 16
months over Jewish settlement construction and a long-overdue
Israeli redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
