<HEADLINE> Ugandan Taxi Drivers Vow to Go on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Taxi drivers and operators here
have vowed to continue to defy government order urging them to
resume normal operations after a two-day strike forcing thousands
of people to go to work on foot or by hired motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
They said they will only go back to transport people if
Minister for Transport, Works and Housing John Nasasira meets
them, Radio Uganda reported Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The report said the taxi drivers and operators have been on
strike because they think the fines to be paid by taxis which
would have caused fatal accidents as stipulated in the new
Traffic and Road Safety Act 1998 are too harsh and too
exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
They warned that it is unwise for government to order
government registered vehicles to ferry people saying that these
could be targets for attack because the move is aimed at breaking
their strike before a solution is found.
</P>
<P>
Many taxi operators who wanted to continue with their normal
operations were threatened off the road by a few misguided
elements who would wish to take law in their hands.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued Tuesday, however, the minister said
the traffic bill was extensively discussed with all Taxi
Operators' Organizations and debated by Parliament before it was
passed.
</P>
<P>
He urged Taxi Operators to resume their operations and warned
individuals bent on disrupting taxi operations to stop forthwith.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will ensure the rule of law and all
those willing to carry out normal business will be protected.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which shut down some of the economy here, was
designed to have been launched at the same time as the first
national congress of the ruling National Resistance Movement was
held in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The strike has spotlighted the shortcomings in the nation's
transport policy. Uganda is peculiar because it is one of the few
countries in the world without a publicly owned mass transport
system and relies exclusively on private buses and taxis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
