<HEADLINE> Zambian Union Rejects Plan to Lay off Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Civil Servants Union of Zambia
(CSUZ) Tuesday dismissed a government plan to lay off about
59,000 Civil servants within two years as "over-ambitious",
saying it would become a source of problems.
</P>
<P>
CSUZ General Secretary Japhet Moonde said the Public Service
Reform program (PSAR) has failed to take off because of the
government's over-ambitious stance of laying off nearly 60,000
workers within two years, Zambia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has no money ready to pay the workers
to be laid off and has resorted to the so-called voluntary
separation package which is meager.
</P>
<P>
The package is also dogged with numerous problems especially
with the insistence by the government that even civil servants
who have worked for over 10 years should register for the
exercise, Moonde said.
</P>
<P>
He said the package should be improved by increasing such
things as repatriation packages from the current 1.5 million
Kwacha (about 750 U.S. Dollars) across the board to about five
million Kwacha (about 2,500 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government and the unions will soon set up a public
service reform program monitoring committee to iron out the
problems in the exercise, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moonde described the dialog with the government as good and
said the union will not want to be seen to be castigating the
government, but trying to ensure that retrenched people lead
meaningful lives. 
