<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Considers to Use Emergency Funds to Help Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior official from the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) is showing the first signs of a
cash shortage, indicating to tap an emergency fund to meet its
latest 11 billion U.S. dollar commitment to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Stanley Fischer, the IMF's first deputy managing director, said
that senior officials from the United States and other major
industrial nations have indicated they would approve a request to
use an IMF emergency fund, called the General Agreement to Borrow
(GAB), to provide some of the money for Russia, according to an AP
report here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The emergency fund was established in 1962 by the major
industrial countries to provide a source of emergency financing
for the IMF, particularly if the major industrial nations needed
it or the IMF's ability to provide credit elsewhere was impaired.
</P>
<P>
It has been tapped only nine times since it was created, the
last time in 1978 by the United States to prop up a staggering
dollar, according to IMF officials.
</P>
<P>
The IMF move came as the White House and the State Department
urged Congress to end months of delay and approve the Clinton
administration's request for a new 18 billion dollar U.S.
contribution to the IMF. The Senate approved the request in March
and a House Appropriations Committee panel is expected to consider
it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government officials have repeatedly argued that the
182-nation IMF's rescue packages promote global economic stability
and enable countries that are markets for U.S exports to recover
from financial crises.
</P>
<P>
The House panel may slice off 3.5 billion dollars of the
administration request for quick approval. The other 14.5 billion
dollars might be delayed until the fall, when the IMF holds its
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
The IMF announced Monday it will provide about 11.2 billion
dollars in additional credit to Russia on top of an existing 9.2
billion dollar loan. Of the new credit, 5.6 billion dollars will
be made available this year.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said the IMF wanted to use 8.4 billion dollars of the
23 billion dollars available in the emergency GAB fund for part of
the payment to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Since the Asian financial crisis erupted last summer, the IMF
has committed 32 billion dollars to help rescue Thailand,
Indonesia and South Korea. And just last week, Indonesia said it
needed 4 billion to 6 billion dollars in additional help.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus and other senior fund
officials have warned they had only 10 billion to 15 billion
dollars left before having to take extraordinary measures such as
tapping the emergency GAB.
</P>
<P>
There are the 23 billion dollar emergency fund and the
multinational agency's 26 billion dollars equivalent in gold that
could be used as collateral to borrow in global financial markets.
In the past Germany, Japan and Italy have resisted any use of IMF
gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
In the Clinton administration's request to Congress for new IMF
funding, 3.5 billion dollars would go to a new emergency fund
called the New Agreement to Borrow or NAB. U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin proposed establishing the NAB after the 1994-1995
Mexican peso crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Electoral Bill Tabled in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A comprehensive electoral
bill to regulate the running of future South African elections at
all governmental tiers was tabled in parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bill provides, among other things, for the electoral
commission to manage all elections, South African Press
Association reported.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum to the draft legislation, tabled by Home Affairs
Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi, points out that a major difference
between the 1994 national and provincial elections and those to
be held next year was that the constitution now requires the
establishment and use of a national voters' roll.
</P>
<P>
The bill further provides that the state president, or premier
of a province, must, when proclaiming an election, give at least
60 days' notice of the voting day.
</P>
<P>
The electoral commission must prescribe the polling hours and
may lay down different ones for different voting stations.
</P>
<P>
It may, on the voting day, extend the hours at a particular
station until midnight and may temporarily close a booth for part
of a day.
</P>
<P>
The electoral commission is to be charged with dividing the
country into voting districts and the bill lays down the factors
that must be taken into account.
</P>
<P>
Each voting district should have between 1,000 (in rural
areas) and 3,000 voters (in urban areas). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
