<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Restricts Travel by Belarus Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States announced
Tuesday it would impose visa restrictions on President Alexander
Lukashenko and other Belarussian leaders because of its dispute
with Belarus over the U.S. ambassador's residence in Minsk.
</P>
<P>
"Each travel request, except those to international
organizations in the United States, will be examined with the
presumption of denial," said State Department spokesman James
Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the last straw in the dispute came last week when
the Belarussians tore down the fence around the U.S. ambassador's
residence, which is inviolate under the Vienna Convention on the
treatment of diplomats.
</P>
<P>
"This new violation was tantamount to forceable seizure of a
diplomatic compound," he said. "Such behavior cannot be
tolerated."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that at this stage the visa ban covered only the
Belarus officials, not members of their families.
</P>
<P>
"They'd like to be able to travel to Europe and the United
States. And so this stings well beyond their ability to impinge on
our effective operation in Belarus," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said he hoped the dispute would not lead to a
break in relations but this was up to Belarus.
</P>
<P>
"The actions of the Belarussian government have effectively
brought our relationship to a standstill and they know what they
need to do to return to a more normal relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously, we will be looking at additional options. But I'm
not going to speculate at what they might be," he said.
</P>
<P>
The European Union took similar measures Monday against a list
of 131 Belarussian ministers and officials, including Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
Ambassadors from the EU countries and the U.S. left Minsk last
month after Belarus said it needed to repair the sewer and water
facilities around the areas and decided to cut off their water and
telephones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
