<HEADLINE> Uganda Launches National Debate on Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has launched a national
debate on what should be the moral and ethical broadcasting
standards.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, which held here Tuesday afternoon, was presided
over by Minister of State in the President's office in charge of
information Basoga Nsadhu, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
The debate is seeking a national consensus on issues such as
what constitutes morality, pornography, what information would
lead to public insecurity or violence and whether censorship of
the media is justifiable.
</P>
<P>
The minister of state commended the Broadcasting Council for
opening the debate to the public, saying that the government
intends to put in place an integrated program of measures which
have been formulated, with the participation of all stake-holders
in an open discussion.
</P>
<P>
An important step in rebuilding public confidence in the
government is to let people have a say on matters that affect
their lives, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Chairperson of the Council Prof. Tarsis Kabwegyere
appealed to the general public, institutions and personalities to
send their opinions to their council.
</P>
<P>
The Broadcasting Council is a statutory body built by the
Electronic Media Statute 1996 to regulate the electronic media.
It is one of its main functions to set the ethical broadcasting
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
