<HEADLINE> Security Council Concerned About Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday reiterated its call for a political dialogue between the
warring factions in Afghanistan and for a cessation of foreign
interference.
</P>
<P>
After consulting on the latest report by Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on the situation in the country between March and June, the
council adopted a presidential statement deploring the breakdown
of the intra-Afghan talks in Islamabad in May.
</P>
<P>
It urged the parties concerned to stop fighting and to return
without delay to the negotiating table for national reconciliation
and a lasting political settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
According to Annan's report, the suspension of the dialogue and
the apparent start of the annual spring offensives are "alarming
developments."
</P>
<P>
"The Afghan factions are either not ready for serious peace
talks or, worse, are determined to pursue the mirage of a military
solution," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council deplores the fact that military support,
including arms supplies from outside Afghanistan to the warring
factions, continues unabated.
</P>
<P>
The council said the United Nations, as a universally
recognized intermediary, must continue to play its central and
impartial role in international efforts towards a peaceful
resolution of the Afghan conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
