<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Faces "Peak Years" of Debt Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Romania has to pay back 2.1
billion U.S. dollars owed to foreign creditors this year and 2.7
billion dollars next year.
</P>
<P>
The amounts due, released lately by the National Bank of
Romania, are turning 1998 and 1999 into "peak years" for the
country's debt payment efforts.
</P>
<P>
Of Romania's total 8.2 billion dollars debt, 64 percent are
long-term credits with maturities of over five years, and 34
percent are mature in one to five years.
</P>
<P>
Romanian financial analysts said the effects of the debt are
"marginal," as a big part of the loans have been directed to
consumption and the balance of foreign payments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they said, credit needs for the expansion of the
country's manufacturing operations are mostly neglected.
</P>
<P>
However, what makes the International Monetary Fund (IMF), one
of Romania's largest creditors, worry is its overburdening with
foreign loans, shown by the growing deficit in its balance of
payments.
</P>
<P>
The deficit last year stood at 2.6 billion dollars, 7 percent
of the country's gross domestic product (GDP); and it is expected
to hike this year to 3.5 billion dollars, 7.8 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Most of foreign credits came from international institutions,
such as the IMF, the International Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development,
and the European Investment Bank.
</P>
<P>
Romania also received financing from the European Union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
