<HEADLINE> India Rejects Proposal for Regional Test Ban Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- India Wednesday rejected
Pakistan's proposal for discussion of a regional nuclear test ban
pact.
</P>
<P>
It is redundant and India is committed to its avowed objective
of working towards a global nuclear disarmament regime, an
External Affairs Ministry spokesman said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the issue of nuclear disarmament in the regional
context does not really work, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan High Commissioner to India Ashraf Jehangir Qazi said
in an interview with the Press Trust of India (PTI) here on
Tuesday that Islamabad is willing to discuss a regional nuclear
text ban pact with India when the two countries' prime ministers
meet on the fringes of the summit of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in Colombo, Sri Lanka, on July
29-31.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The Indian spokesman said that India has already announced a
moratorium on its nuclear tests and expressed willingness for its
de jure formalization. 
</P>
