- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Plans to shut down the Chernobyl nuclear power plant
may be delayed if the funding for building two new plants is not
made available, the Ukrainian cabinet said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government's promise of closing Chernobyl by the
end of 2000 was made under the premise that the Group of Seven and
NATO provide aid for building two new plants, a cabinet statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Aid was also needed to improve the safety of the sarcophagus,
the shield encasing the nuclear reactor and settle social security
concerns once Chernobyl is closed, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
Since the aid was long overdue, the Ukrainian government had to
hinge the closure of the Chernobyl upon the completion of the two
new nuclear plants, the statement said. (BC-Ukraine-Chernobyl)
</P>
