<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Organ Donation Lags Far Behind Demand in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada has one of the worst
organ-donation rates in the western world, Canada's leading daily
newspaper "The Globe and Mail" reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of Canadian patients waiting for transplants has
soared by 68 percent in the past decade, but the number of
transplants has increased only 40 percent during the same period,
despite dramatic technological advances.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's organ-donation rates rank among the lowest of all
developed countries," Dr. Paul Greig, chairman of the Canadian
Organ Replacement Register said, "for example, in 1996, Canada's
rate was only 14.1 donors per million population compared to
Spain's rate of 26.8 donors per million."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, there were only 689 organ donors in Canada, down three
percent from the previous year. Of those donating, 423 were from
brain-dead patients, 266 live donators had given kidneys to their
friends or family members.
</P>
<P>
The yawning gap between demand and supply is not a reflection
of the generosity of Canadians, but rather a testament to the lack
of co-ordination in the organ-retrieval field, said Dr. Philip
Belitsky, a transplant surgeon at the Queen Elizabeth II Health
Sciences Center in Halifax.
</P>
<P>
"There have been sincere efforts to enhance donation in a
number of ways, but what is really needed is a sustained, national
initiative," he said.
</P>
<P>
There were 3,072 patients waiting for organ transplant in
Canada at the end of last year. The vast majority, 82 percent of
the patients were waiting for kidneys, other eight percent were
waiting for livers, and four percent for hearts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
