<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, Syria to Build New Pipeline for Carrying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Minister of Oil Amir
Mohammed Rashid said Wednesday that Iraq and Syria have agreed on
building a new pipeline for transporting Iraqi crude oil to the
world market via Syrian territory.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Iraqi News Agency immediately after his
return to Baghdad from a three-day visit to Syria, the oil
minister said the capacity of the new pipeline would be larger
than the current one and would contribute to increasing Iraq's
exporting potentials in the future.
</P>
<P>
The current Iraqi-Syrian pipeline from the Iraqi northern city
of Kirkuk to Syria's Banias export terminal on the Mediterranean
has been closed since 1982. This happened during the Iran-Iraq war
(1980-88), in which Syria sided with Iran.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said the two countries have agreed on putting the
current Iraqi pipeline across Syria back into full operation,
stressing that pumping of crude oil through the pipeline would
start in a short time.
</P>
<P>
Any reopening of the pipeline system would need the approval of
the U.N. Sanctions Committee on Iraq, though the U.N. has allowed
Iraq's limited oil sales to buy food, medicine and other
humanitarian goods for its people since 1996.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Iraq and Syria signed a memorandum of
understanding under which Kirkuk-Banias pipeline will be reopened.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi Oil Ministry source said on Tuesday that 80 million
U.S. dollars would be needed to repair the old pipeline inside the
Iraqi territory in order to bring it back to its original capacity
of 1.2 million barrels per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
