<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Merapi Volcano Still Spewing Hot Clouds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Merapi volcano, which
erupted last Saturday, is still spewing hot clouds and ashes,
remaining a threat to residents of its surrounding areas, the
Antara News Agency reported Wednesday quoted observers as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hot clouds and gases were still flowing down westward
threatening the village of Krinjing in Dukun sub-district, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"In anticipation of possible danger from hot clouds and lava,
local residents of Krinjing village and officers at the Babadan
observation outpost have been warned to be more vigilant," said
Agus I, Krinjing village head.
</P>
<P>
Merapi erupted at 4:38 local time last Saturday and volcanic
ash hit areas as far as 60 kilometers west and southwest of the
volcano, but no casualty has been reported.
</P>
<P>
"Generally the volcanic activity has decreased but the mountain
is still producing hot gases and clouds," Mas Atje Purbawinata,
head of the Yogyakarta volcanology office said.
</P>
<P>
Merapi lies in Central Java, one of the world's most densely
populated areas. but residents in the ancient royal capital of
Yogyakarta, a city of 2 million people, said they were not
affected by the fresh volcanic activity.
</P>
<P>
Residents of villages near the volcano have been warned to get
ready for evacuation and dams have been built to channel the lava
if it begins to flow in earnest.
</P>
<P>
In November 1994, 60 people were killed when Merapiit Volcano
erupted without warning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
