<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Suffers from Scorching Heat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing heat wave in Shanghai
has forced tens of thousands of local residents to seek the
comfort of the city's some 1,000 air conditioned buses.
</P>
<P>
"We've carried some 500,000 passengers daily over the past few
days," according to an official with the bus line.
</P>
<P>
Drivers and conductors operating the air conditioned buses have
worked 16 hours a day during the period, with the volume of
passengers forcing many to have meals on their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Other passengers have exhibited a preference to stand on buses
with no air conditioning rather than sit in the searing
heat on benches awaiting better equipped units.
</P>
<P>
While weather forecasts continually warn residents of danger
surrounding temperatures of over 38 degrees Celsius, the vast
majority of the 4,000 traffic policemen remain at their posts.
</P>
<P>
"This is an extremely important line of communication, with a
daily traffic flow of more than 70,000 motor vehicles," said Qiu
Weibin, a traffic policeman on Hengshan Road. "I can't imagine
what it would be like without a policeman, even for only a minute."
</P>
<P>
Traffic has flowed smoothing and no major accidents have been
reported during the period, according to the city public security
bureau.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists visiting the Bund has continued to grow
during the evening hours, with many lingering into the early
morning hours to enjoy the comparatively cool air blowing in from
the sea, according to Wei Ruifang, a street cleaner in the
district.
</P>
<P>
"We often collect more than 70 bags of garbage at night," said
Wei, adding that the bags are normally filled with cans and
various types of packaging materials.
</P>
<P>
On the brighter side, the scorching heat has been a blessing
for some local businessmen. For example, the New World Department
Store on prosperous Nanjing Road has sold some 800 air
conditioners over the past three days alone, with the store's
daily turnover soaring to around 500,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city's major ice cream suppliers and watermelon vendors
have also been busy satisfying the heavy demand from local
residents.
</P>
<P>
Many residents in the densely populated southern part of the
city pass their time outside in the early evening hours by
talking, playing chess or drinking beer.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a really hard summer since we have to move before
long," according to septuagenarian Gu Xiuying as he passed out ice
sucker to his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Nanjing and Wuhan, located in the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River, have also suffered from the same scorching heat
over the past week, with highest temperatures reaching 39 degrees
Celsius.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0089 </DOCNO>
