<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say Fungi May Kill Sea Coral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists say they have
discovered fungi that have been killing a type of sea coral from
the Florida Keys to El Salvador over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the July 9 issue of Nature, John W. Taylor from the
University of California at Berkeley and colleagues said they have
found the fungus Aspergillius sydowii has been sickening sea-fan
coral.
</P>
<P>
The fungus, identified through genetic studies of infected
coral, has been present in the Caribbean for years but appears to
have begun killing coral on a large scale only recently.
</P>
<P>
One possibility, they say, is the pollution-caused stress has
made the coral more vulnerable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
