<HEADLINE> Turkish Leaders Condemn Rebels' Killing of 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish leaders Wednesday strongly
condemned the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) for killing 17
Turkish security staff members in an ambush in eastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
President Suleyman Demirel said in a statement that "I'm
strongly condemning this treacherous attack" launched by the PKK
rebels on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place when a group of PKK militants ambushed
the security guards who were on the way for duty near Kamisli
village 10 kilometers from Yuksekova town of Hakkari province
bordering Iran, leaving two officers, eight soldiers and seven
village guards dead.
</P>
<P>
The rebels fled the scene after the killing, while the security
forces launched a large-scale search.
</P>
<P>
Parliament Speaker Hikmet Cetin has also strongly denounced the
attack.
</P>
<P>
In his message to Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi,
Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz expressed his "deep worry" about the
PKK ambush and strongly condemned the terrorist activities by the
Kurdish militants.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz sent letters of condolence to the families of those who
were killed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting the Turkish government since 1984 in
an attempt to establish an "independent Kurdish state" in eastern
and southeastern Turkey. Over 35,000 people, including government
troops, civilians and PKK rebels, have been killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
