<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al Assad will
visit Egypt on Saturday for talks with his Egyptian counterpart
Hosni Mubarak on the Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Assad will arrive in Cairo after his three-day visit to France
which will start on Thursday, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will discuss the current situation regarding
the stalled Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Assad's travel to France, his first outside the region since he
met U.S. President Bill Clinton in Geneva in January 1994, is
reportedly aimed at seeking an alternative to the U.S. mediation
in Syria's negotiations with Israel that have gone nowhere for
more than two years.
</P>
<P>
Assad has refused to resume talks with Israel unless it returns
the occupied Golan Heights to Syria, a term allegedly promised by
Israel's former Labor government led by assassinated Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
With the U.S.-sponsored peace process hitting snags in all
tracks, Arab countries increasingly favor a more active European
diplomacy in reaching a just and comprehensive peace in the
region. 
