<HEADLINE> People's Daily Urges Intensified Battle Against Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Tomorrow's edition of People's
Daily, China's leading newspaper, will carry an editorial calling
for intensified efforts to combat smuggling.
</P>
<P>
China is confronted with rampant smuggling activities which
include the participation of some Party, government and army
organizations, as well as judicial and law enforcement
departments, according to the editorial.
</P>
<P>
The editorial points out that law enforcement personnel have in
some cases accepted bribes or paid fines to protecting smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The editorial stresses that smuggling has caused great harm to
the domestic market and the national industries, caused
substantial losses of tax revenues, violated government
import-export management policies, corrupted officials and
poisoned social morals.
</P>
<P>
"The general public must fully realize that the anti-smuggling
drive is not only a major economic struggle, but also a harsh
political struggle which will have great bearing on the reform,
opening-up and modernization drive," the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
Oil products, automobiles and cigarettes represent major items
involving smuggling activities in coastal areas and inland border
areas, the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
It calls for stress on major smuggling cases and calls for
relentless punishment for Party, government and army units
involved in related activities, as well as for judicial and law
enforcement departments protecting smugglers.
</P>
<P>
It notes the state will standardize anti-smuggling practices
and for a national anti-smuggling police force.
</P>
<P>
The editorial calls for Party organizations and governments at
all levels to join in a concerted effort to "unify thoughts and
actions in line with the strategy and policies of the Central
Party Committee and the State Council, and to ensure that related
strategies and policies are carried out to the letter."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
