<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey might put quotas on some goods from European
Union (EU) countries to retaliate for an EU decision to cancel
privileges to Turkish goods, the Turkish Daily News reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We also have to reciprocate by putting quotas on goods coming
from the European Union," Fuat Miras, chairman of the Turkish
Union of Chambers and Commodity Exchange, was quoted by the
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The EU has decided to suspend privileges bestowed upon Turkey's
ketchup, watermelon and hazelnut due to its plan to halt imports
of meat from EU members for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Cairo Chamber of Commerce has announced that the
number of stores that intend to take part in the upcoming
one-month Tourism and Shopping Festival has increased to 539, the
Egyptian Gazette reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The stores are required to pay 90,000 Egyptian pounds (26,470
U.S. dollars) for the participation in the festival starting on
July 20 as part of Egypt's efforts to rejuvenate its depressed
tourism.
</P>
<P>
According to the chamber's secretary general, the majority of
the stores, which will offer key discounts of up to 50 percent,
are selling leather goods and ready-to-wear garments.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Central Bank has said that Egypt's
foreign exchange reserves reached 20.88 billion dollars last
April, the Egyptian Gazette reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This shows an increase of 442 million dollars from those in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly journal, the bank said the total volume of the
domestic liquid funds in April amounted to 203.7 billion pounds
(59.9 billion dollars), against 202.84 billion pounds (59.66
dollars) in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
