<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore PM Urges Companies to Open Outside-Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 15 (Xinhua)--Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok
Tong Wednesday evening urged companies in the city-state to open
markets outside the region to cope with the worsening regional
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at the Singapore Quality Award (SQA) presentation,
the prime minister said "since falling regional demand has dragged
down our economic growth we will turn our energies towards markets
outside our region."
</P>
<P>
The regional economic situation will get worse before economic
recovery comes about, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the external economic environment has
deteriorated sharply over the last 12 months and the regional
crisis has taken a significant toll on the Singapore economy.
</P>
<P>
He referred to the facts that the mammoth economy of Japan has
entered into recession and South Korea, Thailand, Indonesia,
Malaysia and Hong Kong have all slipped into negative growth in
the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
On the economy of his country, Goh Chok Tong said that the
economic growth has slowed down from 7.8 percent last year to a
newly-revised forecast of 0.5 to 1.5 per cent of this year.
</P>
<P>
Quoting statistics by the country's Productivity and Standard
Board, the prime minister said 70 percent of local small- and
medium-size businesses have projected a drop in sales over the
next six months.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the government's promise to do what is necessary
and practical to stimulate domestic economic activities and
lighten the costs of doing business in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Companies should reassess their old strategies to position
themselves for the future and have to restructure their business
activities and refocus on their core strengths and consolidate
with an eye on the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SQA is presented to recognize organizations that have
attained a commendable level of performance based on the Singapore
Quality Award criteria and are committed to attaining world-class
standards of business excellence. It is developed with inputs and
advice from international experts associated with the U.S. Malcolm
Baldrige National Quality Award, Japan's Deming Prize and the
European Quality Award.
</P>
<P>
Philips Singapore Pte. Ltd., a tuner factory, is the 1998 SQA
winner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
