<HEADLINE> Canada Not to Participate in Hockey Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The scheduling of the first world
under-18 hockey championships next March means Canada won't be
sending a team, a report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The tournament is fixed to be held in Germany in March, when
Canadian major-junior playoffs are in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Canada protested that the timing would make it impossible to
field a competitive team. It wanted the tournament to be held
early September.
</P>
<P>
However, the International Ice Hockey Federation (IIHF) ignored
Canada's objections at meetings in June, and the matches will go
on as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Bob Nicholson, senior vice president of Canadian Hockey, said
he would rather drop out than spend the money to send a
substandard team.
</P>
<P>
Pulling the players off the Canadian Hockey League's
major-junior teams during the playoffs is out of the question, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yet, Kimmo Leinonen, director of public relations for the IIHF,
said he hopes Canada will change its mind.
</P>
<P>
"Any time Canada is not participating, then it is not a real
championship...Canada makes the tournament," he was quoted as
saying by the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The IIHF and Canada are still discussing the issue and that it
will no doubt come up at the federation's semi-annual congress
this September in Toronto, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
