<HEADLINE> NPC Chairman Meets Irish Parliamentary Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the Standing
committee of the Chinese National People's Congress ( NPC), said
today that China is willing to join hands with Ireland to explore
new means and sectors for cooperation in order to elevate
bilateral relations to a new high.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a meeting with an Irish parliamentary
delegation, Li noted that the obvious geographical separation
between China and Ireland has failed to hamper continuous
improvements in relations since the two nations forged diplomatic
ties in 1979. He said that contacts on various levels have, in
fact, been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Seamus Pattison, speaker of the House of
Representatives, is paying an official goodwill visit to China at
the invitation of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China values the role the European Union plays in
both international and regional affairs. He said the world is
marching towards multi-polarization and stressed that the EU will
constitute an important political and economic force.
</P>
<P>
China is pleased to see the development of its relations with
the EU, said Li. He also expressed hope that the relationship will
witness even more substantial progress.
</P>
<P>
Pattison expressed his admiration of China's rapid development,
and noted that both the Irish Parliament and government attach
great importance to developing their relations with China, and
hope to increase exchanges with China.
</P>
<P>
Pattison invited Li Peng to visit Ireland and Li Peng thanked
him very much and accepted the invitation with pleasure. 
</P>
