<HEADLINE> HK to Speed up Information Technology Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) will continue to work
closely with industry and academia to explore ways to facilitate
the commercialization of the results of research on leading edge
information technology.
</P>
<P>
K. C. Kwong, secretary for Information Technology and
Broadcasting, made these remarks in a written reply to a question
raised by a Legislative Council member here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that currently, institutions funded by the University
Grants Committee maintain close contact with the information
technology industry over research activities.
</P>
<P>
Some institutions have also established independent private
bodies to facilitate technology transfer and commercialization of
the results of research on technological developments, including
information technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said to enhance collaboration between the academic sector
and the information technology industry, the government funding
support is made available through the Industrial Support Fund and
the Research Grants Council under the aegis of the University
Grants Committee.
</P>
<P>
The government has financed a number of projects involving
collaborative efforts between the academic sector and the
information technology industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
One example is the Cyberspace Center established by the Hong
Kong University of Science and Technology to promote and
facilitate the use of the Internet among software developers.
</P>
<P>
The center has produced publications on Internet security and
initiated an Internet Business Consortium for the promotion of
business application of Internet.
</P>
<P>
Another example is the Electronic News Media and publishing
Consortium set up by the Chinese University of Hong Kong for the
local news media industry to promote greater use of electronic
publishing.
</P>
<P>
Through the Research Grants Council, funds are provided for
research projects with the potential of social or economic
application, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, Kwong said that the Research Grants Council has
allocated about 160 million HK dollars (20.5 million U.S. dollars)
to support 344 research projects and five large-scale initiatives
in computer science and information technology.
</P>
<P>
The Research Grants Council also supports the establishment of
Co-operative Research Centers to promote technology transfer
between tertiary institutions and the industry, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
