<HEADLINE> Economic, Pro-Poor Bills Top Estrada's Legislative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
would submit to Congress a legislative agenda focusing on the
revival of the economy, food security and the uplift of the poor's
living standards, a presidential press release said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said the agenda took shape during the second cabinet meeting
called by Estrada in the Presidential Palace Tuesday, 12 days
before the opening of the 11th Congress.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Estrada said he would submit to the new
Congress a legislative agenda that represents the economic,
political and social aspirations of every Filipino, especially the
poor, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the priority measures, proposed by different
cabinet clusters, focused on proposed bills that would address the
projected 70-billion-peso (1.75 billion U.S. dollars) fiscal
deficit through several tax and non-tax measures.
</P>
<P>
The proposals also include measures that would provide the
delivery of quality basic services to the poor, ensure food
security and agricultural productivity, promote investments,
pump-prime the economy and improve peace and order in the country.
</P>
<P>
In the 11th Congress, 12 out of the 24 senators and all the 260
members of the House of Representatives were newly elected in the
May 11 elections in which Estrada was elected the president.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the ongoing Asian financial crisis, the
Philippine economy was severely battered and is expected to grow
by only 2 percent in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
