<HEADLINE> Jordanian Organization Formed to Help Libyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A humanitarian organization was set
up here Wednesday with an aim of flying Libyan patients to Jordan
for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The organization, named as The Humanitarian Commission to Help
the Libyan Patients, issued a statement after its inauguration
saying that it was a non-profitable, non-partisan, non-religious
and non-political organization.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the launching of an air route between Amman
and Tripoli, capital of Libya, can spare Libyan patients from
traveling by land to Tunisia or Egypt to get a flight.
</P>
<P>
The air route will also be used to transport humanitarian
goods to Libya, it added.
</P>
<P>
The proposed direct flight between the two countries has yet to
be approved by the United Nations, which has imposed an air
embargo against Libya since 1992 for its refusal to extradite two
of its citizens suspected of bombing an American airliner in 1988.
</P>
<P>
In the bombing over over Lockerbie, Scotland, 270 people aboard
the Pan Am flight 103 were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian commission was formed in line with Jordan's
efforts in the international arena to help alleviate the
sufferings of the Libyan people caused by the sanctions, the
statement added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
