<HEADLINE> Philippine Government to Resolve PAL Labor Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada said here
Wednesday that the government hopes to resolve the labor dispute
in the Philippine Airlines (PAL) in one to two weeks to save the
airline from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he had instructed Labor Secretary Bienvenido
Laguesma to work for the speedy settlement of the labor problems
that has hobbled Philippine Airlines operations and caused severe
inconvenience to the public.
</P>
<P>
Last month, some 620 pilots went on a strike to protest the
PAL's decision that all pilots must retire after serving the
company for a total of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The strike exacerbated the financial crisis facing the company.
To pay off its two-billion-U.S.-dollar debt, the PAL decided to
reduce its size from 54 airplanes to 14 and sack 5,000 employees,
one third of its employees.
</P>
<P>
However, the pilots continued their strike, putting the airline
on the verge of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada said the timing of the strike was
"particularly unfortunate" in view of the centennial celebration
of the Philippines' independence from Spain.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the labor problem in the PAL has inflicted
damage to the riding public, citing that a pilot was reported to
have even abandoned his passengers in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The PAL, Asia's first airline, was trapped in serious economic
woes as a result of the ongoing Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia May Ratify Landmine Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Foreign Minister
Theo-Ben Gurirab has tabled a proposal in the National Assembly
calling for the ratification of the international landmine
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Most Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries
have concurred with the principle of the Ottawa Convention, which
bans the development, use, stockpiling and transfer of
anti-personnel landmines. But they still have to commit
themselves formally.
</P>
<P>
SADC Executive Secretary Kaire Mbuende said in his review of
the organization's activities over the past few months that so
far only three of the 14-member block -- Mauritius, Mozambique
and South Africa -- had ratified the treaty, South African Press
Association reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ottawa Convention can only become effective after it has
been ratified by 40 countries. Worldwide, only 19 countries have
ratified the document, although 126 countries have signed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
