<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Proposes to Increase WTO Transparency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States has proposed to
increase transparency at the World Trade Organization (WTO),
arguing that the organization's credibility and viability depends
on the public understanding of its role.
</P>
<P>
"The United States wants to open up the WTO, the documents and
the meetings," said Rita Hayes, U.S. permanent representative to
the WTO, when announcing her country's initiative here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. proposal is to be discussed when the General Council
of the 132-member WTO meets on July 15.
</P>
<P>
Hayes said the minutes of General Council meetings generally
come out a month after the events, and even then they are marked
"restricted" and may remain unavailable to the press and general
public for as long as six months.
</P>
<P>
The same problem exists with panel reports, leading to
different interpretations by interested parties who would claim
victory by quoting parts of the reports, she said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO has nothing to fear and everything to gain from
increased transparency, she said.
</P>
<P>
"We could televise meetings of the WTO committees and councils
starting tomorrow, and it would make no difference in the ability
of the organization to do its job," she said.
</P>
<P>
"On the other hand, increased transparency in WTO operations
and a meaningful dialogue with civil society would go a long way
to building support for the system."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade envoy hoped that the General Council will move
to adopt the U.S. proposal immediately but conceded that some
delegations may not yet be "on board." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
