<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Angry voters in Sunday's parliamentary election sent the
ruling Liberal Democratic Party a blunt command to save the
nation's ailing economy, but there is growing concern in Japan
that shocked party members seem more concerned with saving their
own political skin.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian stock prices soared Tuesday in reaction to the 22.6
billion U.S. dollar international bailout plan for Russia, as
President Boris Yeltsin appealed to legislators to pass new reform
measures designed to get the economy in working order.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- A Nigerian opposition leader met with the country's new
military ruler Abubakar, urging him to form a national-unity
government.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Yielding to U.S. farmers facing heavy losses, Congress voted
to exempt agriculture credits from sanctions on India and Pakistan
for exploding nuclear devices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
