<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Largest National Park Set for Himalayas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. nature protection
organization plans to join China in building one of the world's
largest national parks on eastern slopes of the Himalayan
mountains.
</P>
<P>
The nongovernmental association will pump two million
U.S. dollars into the construction of the park which will be
seven times the size of famous Yellowstone National Park
in Wyoming, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Three major rivers -- the Yangtze, Lancang and Nujiang rivers -
meander through the proposed park in southwest China's Yunnan
Province.
</P>
<P>
The area also features famous attractions such as the
snow-covered Yulong Mountains, the Nujiang Great Canyon which
features a 4,000 meter drop in elevation and Hutiao Canyon in the
upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The northwestern part of the province bordering on the
Qinghai-Tibet and Yunnan-Guizhou plateaus features diverse
wildlife. Experts point out that the area is also a sanctuary for
flora, as well as the natural habitat for rare animals species
such as snub-nosed monkeys, black-necked cranes, pandas and
leopards.
</P>
<P>
The ecosystem in the 60,000 sq.km. park will greatly affect the
well-being of residents in the lower reaches of the three river
valleys.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the diverse cultural heritage in the region will
appeal to tourists. For example, Dayan, which has a history of
over 800 years and is home to the Naxi ethnic minority, was listed
as a World Heritage late last year. In addition, idyllic and
picturesque Zhongdian County in the Diqing Tibet Autonomous
Prefecture attracts people from throughout the world seeking the
so-called "Shangri-La".
</P>
<P>
The cultural traditions of the Tibetan, Naxi, Bai and Lisu
nationalities have been well preserved in that area, according to
an official of the association.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based association, which originally hesitated in
joining the massive park project, decided to join in the effort
following on-site visits by members of the organization's board of
directors. The board also decided to establish its Asia
representative office in Kunming.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum agreement signed by the two sides calls for the
association to provide the province with advanced management,
skilled personnel and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The park will cover an area with a total population of over
three million people, and the project will provide job
opportunities for some 1.5 million local residents.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have introduced regulations prohibiting
timbering in the area and have adopted various initiatives to
encourage tourism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
