<HEADLINE> Malaysian Minister to Discuss Economic Crisis With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUAAL LUMPUR, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister and Finance Minister Anwar Ibrahim will leave for the
United States Thursday to hold meetings with the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on the economic crisis in
Asia and Malaysia, according to an official statement Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who will be in Washington for four days, will gather
views on the best ways to revive the economies in the region, a
finance ministry statement issued here said.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who was appointed chairman of the World Bank/IMF
Development Committee in April this year for the next two years,
will exercise his duties as the committee chairman during his stay
in Washington, it said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been seriously affected by the economic crisis in
Asia with its gross domestic product (GDP) falling by 1.8 percent
in the first quarter this year and the whole year's GDP growth
projected officially to be negative 1 to 2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
