<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Rejects Changes in U.S. Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) ruled out Wednesday its acceptance of any changes
in the U.S. proposal on Israel's next troop redeployment in the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Chief PNA negotiator Saeb Erekat, in an interview with the Voice
of Palestine, said the PNA could accept the U.S. proposal to have
direct talks with Israel, but will never agree to any changes in
the U.S. initiative calling for a 13.1 percent Israeli pullback.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that arrangement was being made for holding a
meeting between PNA deputy head Abu Mazen and Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the PNA would never make any more compromise
on the U.S. proposal, which it has already adopted. Israel has so
far rejected the U.S. plan citing that any redeployment exceeding
9 percent would endanger its security interests.
</P>
<P>
Erekat disclosed that the U.S. had renewed a promise to announce
its proposal in the near future, probably in one week's time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu reconvened
the "Kitchen Cabinet" Wednesday morning to discuss the
redeployment issue and the situation facing the peace process. No
decision was made.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet, which also includes Mordechai, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon and Industry and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky, had already held several sessions before
in an attempt to take a decision on the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the Wednesday meeting, the cabinet
expressed welcome to the U.S. idea on resuming the direct
Israeli-Palestinian talks. The U.S. has demanded PNA President
Yasser Arafat to have direct talks with Mordechai, if not
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The PNA earlier rejected this request, saying the U.S. had not
specified what issues to be discussed during the talks and it
would not attend such talks without any concrete promise by the
Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled for 16
months since March 1997 because of Israeli policies of expanding
settlements and refusing to carry out the long overdue troop
redeployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
