<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Anti-Smuggling System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said
here today that China will establish a national special police
force to combat smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing session of the national anti-smuggling
work conference, Zhu said China will introduce measures to
intensify the crack down on smuggling in China.
</P>
<P>
The special force, which will operate under the joint guidance
of customs administrations and public security departments, will
conduct smuggling investigations, arrest culprits involved and
conduct preliminary hearing involving related cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
Public security will join customs and industrial and commercial
administrations in activities to eradicate smuggling, according
to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He said all fines and proceeds earned from smuggled goods will
be handed over to the central government.
</P>
<P>
The central government will receive 30 percent of the total
proceeds in the form of taxes, with some 50 percent of the
remainder used to equip anti-smuggling departments and reward
individuals and departments contributing to the effort. Remaining
funds will go to help provincial government battle smuggling,
according to Zhu.
</P>
<P>
He said that all Party and government offices, law enforcement
agencies and judiciary departments will sever relations with
affiliate companies, and conduct thorough investigations related
to smuggling activities conducted by related organizations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that the State Council will examine all
anti-smuggling efforts.
</P>
<P>
He touched upon the current economic situation in China and
noted that further development of the national economy will
represent a major achievement in light of the ongoing financial
crisis in Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
