<HEADLINE> Chinese City Reports Increase In Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEIHAI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Weihai in east
China's Shandong Province approved 61 overseas-funded enterprises
in the first five months of this year, with contracted overseas
investment totaling 87.9 million U.S. dollars, an increase of 45.5
percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Paid-in overseas investment in Weihai amounted to 77 million
U.S. dollars in the January-May period, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
To counter the effects of the Asian financial crisis, Weihai
this year has looked to Europe and North America for overseas
capital instead of the Republic of Korea and other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Between January and May, investment from Japan, the ROK, and
other Asian sources dropped 23 percentage points on a yearly
basis, while investment from Europe, America, and Oceania rose
46.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a similar development, overseas investors already in Weihai
added more than 20 million U.S. dollars to 18 projects in the
first five months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
