<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Russia Discuss Security Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Russian security
officials Wednesday discussed Israel's concern over the alleged
transfer of missile technology to Iran by Russian companies,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Foreign Ministry sources as saying that
Director of the Russian Federal Security Service (RFSS) Nikolai
Kovalev was visiting Israel to discuss Israel's demand that Russia
do more to stop transferring missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also discuss cooperation in fighting
organized crimes and international terrorism, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The RFSS, one of several successors of the former Soviet
Union's secret intelligence service the KGB, is Russia's major
counterintelligence and anti-terrorism agency.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli newspaper Haaretz reported Wednesday that Kovalev
arrived in Israel on Monday for a five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Industry and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky and his Israeli counterparts, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Kovalev is the first senior Russian security official to visit
Israel.
</P>
<P>
A western source was quoted by the paper as saying that his
visit marks "a new Russian desire to play a bigger role in the
Middle East than it has since the end of the Cold War."
</P>
<P>
Kovalev's visit came amid Israel's doubts about whether Russia
has done enough to halt the flow of ballistic missile technology
to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security officials complained that although the Russian
government "has done much more than it has in the past," it fails
to completely halt the transfer of missile technology to Iran by
Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
Israel has expressed concern that its archrival Iran will
acquire sufficient technology next year to produce its own
prototype for surface-to-surface missiles that can hit the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
