<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed up Wednesday but failed to maintain the early momentum
sparked by overnight gains on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index drifted from an intra-day
high of 2,797.5 to close at 2,773.9.
</P>
<P>
Steven Carroll, an expert, said the 149.33 point overnight gain
in the Dow Jones Industrial Average to 9,245.54 fueled early gains
on the local bourse.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all industrials index
closed 15.6 points firmer at 4,849.2, while the all resources
index stacked on 25.9 points to close at 1,102.3.
</P>
<P>
Among resource leaders, Australian resources giant BHP closed
33.9 cents firmer at 14.76 Australian dollars, a 2.35 percent
gain, and global miner Rio Tinto picked up 41.9 cents to finish
19.32 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index jumped 12.2 points to 1,087.0 on slightly firmer
gold prices.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney closed at 292.75 U.S.
dollars, compared with a close of 292.35 U.S. dollars Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank index was 30.3 points higher to close at 6066.8.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank jumped 9.4 cents to 22.73 Australian
dollars, ANZ bank gained 8.7 cents to 11.40 Australian dollars,
Westpac bank picked up 6.5 cents to 10.50 Australian dollars and
the Commonwealth Bank of Australia rose six cents to 20.10
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover figures show 288.44 million shares were
traded for 613.49 million U.S. dollars, with rising stocks
outnumbering falling stocks 643 to 454. 
</P>
</TEXT>
