<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Auction For Commercial Uses In Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
will abolish government approval procedures for transfers of land
for commercial purpose as of August 1, 1998 and open commercial
land-use rights to public bidding.
</P>
<P>
This will mean a great change in Guangdong's approval
procedures, Yuan Zhengjie, director of the Guangdong Provincial
Land Administration Department, told a press conference today, and
will allow the market, not some particular individual, to decide
the final price of land.
</P>
<P>
Land developers in Guangdong used to obtain land-use rights
from the government directly and it was easy for corrupt officials
to influence the price of land.
</P>
<P>
The province began reforming the approval procedure in 1987,
but only 5 percent of the land for commercial development has been
auctioned publicly since then.
</P>
<P>
According to recent government regulations, all land to be used
for housing, shops, hotels and entertainment facilities will be sold
at public auctions from the beginning of next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
