<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tops Developing Countries in Attracting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China tops developing countries
in attracting direct foreign investment with its share reaching
about 45 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, the Arab Institution for
Investment Insurance (AIII) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The AIII's report showed that Brazil came as the second by
attracting some 10 billion dollars of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
It said that last year has witnessed an increase in the flow of
direct foreign investment in the world, which amounted to 364
billion dollars, a 4 percent hike over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Available statistics showed that approximately 84 percent of
the investment originated from the bloc of industrialized
countries.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the geographic distribution of this flow, the
industrialized countries took the lion's share, or some 60
percent, while the developing countries received only about 38
percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The share of developing countries of the total direct foreign
investment has increased to 135 billion dollars in 1997 from 129
billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Divided to regions, the share of the developing countries in
southeastern Asia was 85.1 billion dollars, or 63.3 percent of the
total. The Latin American and Caribbean states attracted about
13.5 billion dollars, while the share of African states was below
4 billion dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the share of Arab states of direct foreign
investment stood at about 6 billion dollars, or 4.4 percent of the
total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
