<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Leader Seeks Normalization with World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has expressed the determination of the nation
to normalize relations with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
It was Nigeria's desire to be more involved in world affairs
so as to contribute its quota to the cause of international peace
and the collective security of mankind, he said.
</P>
<P>
The head of state made the remarks at a meeting Tuesday with
Mamoudou Lamine Jobe, foreign minister of Gambia, who was in the
Nigerian capital Abuja as special envoy of President Yahaya
Jammeh to deliver a special message to Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
According to Abubakar, who became head of state of the most
populous African country on June 9, the international community
must work relentlessly for the cause of peace and collective
security of mankind.
</P>
<P>
He particularly appealed to the warring factions in Guinea
Bissau to go to the negotiation table for an amicable resolution
of their differences.
</P>
<P>
Receiving Cavaye Djibril, president of the national assembly
(parliament) of Cameroun, in Abuja last week, Abubakar urged
African leaders to work relentlessly toward achieving peace and
harmony within the continent.
</P>
<P>
The leaders should seek more mature, humane and diplomatic
means of settling disputes as "Africa is tired of wars", he said,
adding Nigeria would continue to live at peace with its
neighboring states in the true spirit of African solidarity and
brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's remarks are seen by observers here as a kind of
indication of the new government's foreign relations position.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has been in the eye of the storm with the
international community since the regime of former Head of State
General Ibrahim Babangida annulled the June 12, 1993 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Its relations with the rest of the world worsened in November
1995 with the hanging of Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight of his Ogoni
kinsmen.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth in its reaction suspended Nigeria's
membership, while the United States and the European Union
imposed a string of sanctions on the country.
</P>
<P>
Following the sudden death on June 8 of the former Head of
State General Sani Abacha and the assumption of power by General
Abubakar, the heads of the United Nations and the Commonwealth,
Kofi Annan and Emeka Anyaoku, U.S. Under-Secretary of State for
Political Affairs Thomas Pickering and British Deputy Foreign
Minister Tony Lloyd visited Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
These VIPs came to parley with Nigerian officials on the
future of democracy, human rights and the release of political
detainees, which are all issues critical to the military
government's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
It is widely accepted that the strings of visits have helped
build good fame for Abubakar both within and outside the country
and re-open the country to Western countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
