<HEADLINE> Sweden: Consumer Price Index Down in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Consumer Price Index (CPI) was
up 0.6 percent in June over the same month last year, but grew at
a slower pace compared to the 0.9 percent rise in May.
</P>
<P>
"The figure was somewhat lower than expected... This opens the
door for rate cuts," said economist Sharder Persaud, commenting on
the inflation gauge released by Statistics Sweden on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Discounts on shoes and clothing, as shown by official
statistics, helped curb the index increase in June.
</P>
<P>
As a result, economists now are expecting to see another
interest rate cut by the Swedish Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which follows a price stability target, last time
lowered its key "repurchase rate," or repo rate, to 4.1 percent
after holding it steady for two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
