<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs 50 Bln U.S. Dollars to Revive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B. J. Habibie
Wednesday said that the government needs 10 billion to 11 billion
U.S. dollars while the private sector needs 40 billion dollars to
revive the economy.
</P>
<P>
"It would be impossible for us to restore the economy without
help from others," Habibie told a nationwide meeting of Islamic
boarding school directors here.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) would decide to release the second 3 billion dollar tranche
of its aid to Indonesia when its 24 directors meet in Washington
on July 15 to 18.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has signed a revised bailout
agreement with the IMF on June 24 in a bid to arrest the country's
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The revised agreement paved the way for the resumption of the
43 billion dollar IMF-led rescue package.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia received the first tranche of 3 billion dollars from
the IMF in November last year, but the second disbursement of 3
billion dollars was delayed due to riots in Jakarta in May and the
following political crisis in the country which forced former
president Soeharto to step down.
</P>
<P>
In a two-hour speech, Habibie said international financial
institutions and countries which have pledged funds to rescue
Indonesia from its economic crisis "have the right to judge
whether Indonesia has the credibility that would convince them to
provide what the country needs."
</P>
<P>
He also underscored the importance of unity in implementing
political, economic and judicial reforms to restore the country's
credibility to the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
