<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Opposition Insists on Unity Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's major opposition group
the National Democratic Coalition (NADECO) insists on the
establishment of a national unity government, despite the death
of opposition leader Chief Moshood Abiola.
</P>
<P>
This was made known during a meeting between NADECO and
Nigeria's new military leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar Tuesday
in Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the second between Abubakar and NADECO since
Abubakar started his nationwide consultations on the way forward
a month ago.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting took place on June 27, at which NADECO
proposed a national unity government to be headed by Abiola, the
presumed winner of the June 12, 1993 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
NADECO's chairman Chief Abraham Adesanya told reporters after
Tuesday's meeting that the group's position on the unity
government has not changed, though it was yet to consider anybody
as head of the unity government.
</P>
<P>
Adesanya said there was no agreement reached at the meeting,
but Abubakar has agreed to consider NADECO's stand.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the opposition group also called for the
holding of a sovereign national conference to prepare for a new
constitution by which Nigeria will be ruled.
</P>
<P>
After taking the power in 1993, late military leader General
Sani Abacha has called a national constitutional conference, but
he kept the constitution in his drawer until his sudden death a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
Legally speaking, the country's 1979 constitution is still
valid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa's Vice-President Thambo Mbeki said in
Pretoria Tuesday that Abubakar has agreed to set up a
transitional government during his visit to Nigeria last week.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said, Abubakar is to announce the composition of the
transition government Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
