<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Hit 11 Villages in Southern Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The floods have displaced
inhabitants of 11 villages which stretched between the town of
Balad and the main road linking Mogadishu and Ballidogle Airport,
a local humanitarian group said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Dahir Fidow, Chairman of Al-Hijra Welfare and
Development Organization, a local humanitarian group, expressed
deep concern over the fate of the people in Warabole Village,
about 40 kilometers southeast of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Warabole Village is besieged by water at a height of 1.5
meters to 1.8 meters.
</P>
<P>
"The water is lying two kilometers on every side of this
village," Fidow said, adding that the floods are now heading
toward the three directions of south, southwest and southeast at
a very high speed.
</P>
<P>
"At this rate, the highway between Mogadishu and Ballidogle
Airport, 90 kilometers south of the capital, will be cut off in
less than a week unless something tangible is done against that,"
said Fidow.
</P>
<P>
There are five bridges under which the rain water or floods
passed through, he said, "but now they are blocked by mud and
stones, so that the water can't run beneath them."
</P>
<P>
The road between Mogadishu and Ballidogle has only been
rehabilitated recently after it was destroyed by the heavy floods
last years which killed around 2,000 people and more than 35,000
heads of livestock and devastated at least 60,000 hectares of
farmlands.
</P>
<P>
The floods seriously affected more than half a million people
in the regions of Middle Shabelle, Lower Shabelle, Middle Jubba
and Lower Jubba, Bay and Bakol.
</P>
<P>
There is a growing concern that floods may again devastate
thousands hectares of farmlands and residential areas in several
regions of southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
River Shabelle burst its banks earlir this week near Balad
Town of Middle Shabelle region, 30 kilometers north of the
capital, making the water cross to the Lower Shabelle Region.
</P>
<P>
The travelers from Baidoa and Ballidogle Airport are also
speaking about a large lake-like water being created about 45
kilometers south of the airport submerging most of the trees.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 people including women and children who have
already been displaced by the floods are now scattered in
Lamadonka Village, 42 kilometers south of Mogadishu, and beside
the main road between the capital and Ballidogle airport.
</P>
<P>
The displaced people are seriously suffering because of lack
of food and shelter in this rainy season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
