<HEADLINE> Foreigners Allowed to Withdraw EFP Money Upon Leaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreigners including
Singapore nationals employed in Malaysia can withdraw their
Employees Provident Fund (EPF) contributions even before reaching
the age of 55 upon leaving the country, the EFP said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This special permission, especially for Singaporeans, has been
given since October 1996 under an amendment to the Employees
Provident Fund Act 1991, EPF public relations officer Nik Affendi
Jaafar said, according to Malaysia's national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
As withdrawal is not automatic, foreign workers can submit
applications to take out the contributions before leaving
Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that it was not mandatory for foreign
workers to contribute to the EPF.
</P>
<P>
The EPF contributions, as of last December 31, accumulated to
130.85 billion ringgit (31.53 billion U.S. dollars), according to
the official.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, several parties in Malaysia asked Singapore
to review its ruling disallowing peninsular Malaysians no longer
employed in the republic from withdrawing their Central Provident
Fund (CPF) contributions before reaching 55.
</P>
<P>
Malaysians from Sabah and Sarawak, East Malaysia, like other
foreigners, are, however, exempted from this ruling.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Trades Union Congress (MTUC) President Zainal Rampak
has urged Singapore to amend its CPF laws to enable peninsular
Malaysians no longer working there to automatically withdraw their
CPF contributions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
