<HEADLINE> Malaysian Firm Invited to Buy Ugandan Parastatal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
invited a Malaysian telecommunications giant to negotiate for the
sale of 51 percent of the newly restructured Uganda
Telecommunications Limited (UTL).
</P>
<P>
This decision has been made following the other three of the
four bidders failed to submit their bids by the deadline on July
10, 1998, the New Vision newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Divestiture Reform and Implementation Committee (DRIC),
the cabinet sub-committee on privatization, Tuesday canceled the
bidding process and invited Telekom Malaysia International (TMI)
to enter into direct negotiations with government toward the
purchase of the UTL shares for sale.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Tuesday by the Enterprise Development
Project, a body responsible for privatization in Uganda, said
that at its meeting on July 14, the DRIC reviewed the status of
the UTL privatization.
</P>
<P>
On April 28, 1998, four groups were approved for UTL's 51
percent shares for sale.  
</P>
</TEXT>
