<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Central Bank to Toughen Regulation on Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya
said it was tightening regulations on the banking industry in
order to prepare it for the competitive pressures of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
Most significant of the central bnak's measures were new rules
governing directors' access to lending, the East African Standard
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
CBK said in future loans to directors and senior management
must be sanctioned by the full board of directors, be on similar
terms to those to other customers and be disclosed in published
accounts.
</P>
<P>
"In order to achieve a complete arm's length relationship, a
new proposal will be made in the foreseeable future where
directors will not be permitted to take any loan facility from
the bank on whose board they serve," CBK said in its monthly
economic review for July.
</P>
<P>
If a loan becomes non-performing, a director will be
automatically disqualified from the board. Banks could also be
open to penalties if the banking act is violated, CBK said.
</P>
<P>
In March, the government fired three directors, the general
manager and the executive chairman of Kenya Commercial Bank,
the largest retail bank in East Africa, after local media reported
they had been allowed irregular and unsecured loans.
</P>
<P>
Concerns have been mounting about the extent of non-performing
loans which Kenyan banks are carrying.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans are estimated at 43.8 billion Shillings
(736 million Dollars) at the end of December last year out of an
overall 209 billion Shillings in loans and advances.
</P>
<P>
There are 14 non-bank financial institutions and 53 commercial
banks, of which 26 face the risk of closure next year when a new
banking rule takes effect forcing them to increase their capital
base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
