<HEADLINE> Australian FM Urges Japan to Tackle Economic Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan needs to urgently tackle
its economic problems as the country's recovery is central to the
future of entire Asia, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander
Downer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to a group of Australian exporters in Melbourne,
Downer said the Asian crisis is the most significant external
economic shock to Australia in nearly 20 years, with Japan the
crucial factor in determining when Asia would recover.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of goods and services which Australia exports
go to Asia each year.
</P>
<P>
"The weekend's upper house election result and Prime Minister
(Ryutaro) Hashimoto's subsequent resignation demonstrate the
seriousness of the economic situation in Japan and the urgency
with which Japan's economic problems need to be addressed," Downer
said.
</P>
<P>
"Japanese recovery is central to the fortunes of East Asia. It
is crucial that Japan takes measures to ensure its economy does
not slide into deep recession, seeing further devaluation in the
yen," Downer was quoted by the Australian Associated Press as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Downer, who visited Indonesia last week, warned that Indonesia
would also require international help for at least a year if it is
to overcome its economic and political crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand and South Korea have both been making good
progress in their reforms.
</P>
<P>
Asia would recover and it is important not to be pessimistic
about the region's economic crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The economic strengths which made East Asia highly attractive
to global investors over the past two decades have not
disappeared."
</P>
<P>
"High savings rates continue and an increasingly skilled and
educated workforce will be able to capitalize on the upswing which
will inevitably come in due course," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
