<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria May Announce Transition Government: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new leader General Abdulsalam
Abubakar has agreed to set up a transition government and is expected
to announce the composition of it Thursday.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of what South African Vice-President
Thambo Mbeki told reporters in Pretoria Tuesday on his visit to
Nigeria last week, the official newspaper New Nigerian reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The transition government, according to Mbeki, will handle
constitutional review and coordinate moves toward credible democratic
election activities which the current military regime said would best
be handled by civilian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, during his visit last week, met with the head of state and
some opposition groups in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said the transition government would be set up because the
opposition groups and the authorities wanted to avoid a drift into
ethnic tension.
</P>
<P>
According to Mbeki, South Africa is keenly interested in the
political stability of Nigeria, considering its leading role in Africa
and its size of population.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also quoted South African government sources as
saying that Nigerians regarded South Africa as an honest broker,
despite the sour relations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
There is suspicion about direct involvement of the United States,
Britain and France in the transition program because, unlike South
Africa, they have major commercial interests in Nigeria, the report
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
