<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Chinese Judge Stresses Judicial Openness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) - Judge Xiao Yang, the president of
China's Supreme People's Court, in commenting on China Central
Televsion's recent live broadcast of a civil suit, said that open
trials increase judicial openness, prevent "darkroom operations",
and see to it that justice is served.
</P>
<P>
On July 11, CCTV covered a copyright violation case involving
10 Chinese film studios in Beijing's No. 1 Intermediate People's
Court.
</P>
<P>
Xiao said in an interview today that judicial reforms are an
important part of the political reforms discussed at the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China held last autumn
and an important move by the Supreme People's Court this year to
re-educate judges across the country.
</P>
<P>
Open trials are not, he added, a new invention of the SPC, and,
according to the Chinese Constitution and laws, all trials, except
those involving state secrets, personal privacy, and juveniles,
are open to the public.
</P>
<P>
He explained that some local courts have opened their
proceedings to the media before and the live broadcasts got a good
reception by the public, and he encouraged the courts and media
organizations to continue with this practice.
</P>
<P>
He said that they are also an effective way to protect judicial
independence, and that Chinese courts hear 5.2 million criminal,
civil, economic, and administrative cases annually, and are mostly
independent in their judgements.
</P>
<P>
"However, a few officials in some places do not
properly use their power or they even abuse it," he said, pointing
out that courts, whose personnel and finances are controlled
locally, sometimes have to deal with individual interference and
find it difficult making a fair and independent judgement.
</P>
<P>
"Open trials can curb or eliminate the interference or such
factors as personal favors, power, and money," Xiao concluded, and
said they also help increase public awareness of the law, improve
efficiency and proficiency in the judiciary, and prevent
corruption in law-enforcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
