<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Earnings Off 29 Percent in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corporation reported
Tuesday a 29 percent drop in earnings and a sequentially flat
revenue in the second quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The chip-making giant's second quarter revenue was 5.9 billion
dollars, compared to 6 billion dollars a year ago. Its net income
of the same period stood at 1.2 billion dollars, down 29 percent
from a year ago and 8 percent from the first quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
But the company said in a statement that cost-cutting measures
and new products should boost its revenue in the next quarter.
</P>
<P>
Intel plans to move to the 0.18 micron chipmaking process by
the second quarter of 1999, one quarter earlier than expected.
This will help increase chip yields and allow for the introduction
of newer, faster 32-bit processors.
</P>
<P>
Intel's earning cuts in the first two quarters this year may
verify a cyclical phenomenon of the sector. Computer chip making
has always been a cyclical business, in which improvements in
production may periodically cause oversupply, which in turn drives
down prices and profits.
</P>
<P>
But analysts say the oversupply of computers and
microprocessors now seems to be easing, which may clear the way
for sales, at possibly higher prices in the second half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Intel cautioned today that there will be continual inventory
adjustment as the industry attempts to become more efficient.
</P>
<P>
The company predicted a mild revenue growth in the third quarter
this year and a greater revenue in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
So far, 1988 has not been a banner year for the processor
giant. First-quarter sales slumped because of a slowdown in
computer demand, leading the company to announce a reduction of
3,000 employees. Subsequently, Intel had to put off the release of
its 64-bit Merced chip until 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
