<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Uncompromising Over Wage Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Despite the opposition of a
coalition partner, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz has voted
to reject a wage hike exceeding 20 percent for the public sector,
a newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I would not give half a percentage point more than 20 percent"
to the wage rise for the public sector employees, the Daily News
quoted Yilmaz as telling a meeting of parliament members of his
Motherland Party (ANAP) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Turkey Party, a ruling coalition partner, Monday
demanded that public sector's wages be raised by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
It warned that if the demand was not accepted by ANAP and
another coalition partner Democratic Left Party, its ministers
would not sign the decision on a 20 percent wage hike and would
continue their struggle in the government.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz argued that even a 20 percent wage hike would cost 280
trillion Turkish Liras (about 1.037 billion U.S. dollars), and it
was impossible to finance a 40 percent wage hike from the existing
budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
