<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Irish Police Arrest Bomb-Hurling Orangemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Northern Irish police, firing
rubber bullets, arrested 13 bomb-hurling "hooligans" during a
clash with the Protestant Orangemen on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Police also seized a van in clash with the angry protesters who
were barred from marching down a Catholic area in Portadown, 50 km
south-west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman said on Wednesday that around 10 blast bombs
and petrol bombs were thrown at security forces who responded with
plastic bullets during the night. So far there were no reports of
casualties.
</P>
<P>
He said the violence was the work of a "small group of
hooligans" who had tried to break down barriers erected by
security forces to prevent the Orange Order from carrying out its
planned march along Portadown's mainly Catholic Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
The clashes have continued since July 5, when the Orange Order
began their annual parade in defiance of the ban issued by a
parade commission and stopped by police. The Orange Order has
vowed to walk through the traditional route no matter how long
they have to wait.
</P>
<P>
The violence has threatened to wreck last April's historic
peace agreement intended to draw a line under three decades of
sectarian and political violence in Northern Ireland that has cost
more than 3,600 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
