<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Hails Kiriyenko's Visit to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia called the first visit by
its Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko to Japan a success, saying it
will ensure the development of bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin was quoted by the
Itar-Tass news agency Wednesday as saying that the one-day visit
Monday was marked by "significant practical results."
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Kiriyenko and Japanese leaders discussed
economic cooperation issues, especially cooperation in the
framework of the Yeltsin-Hashimoto plan made in Krasnoyarsk in
late 1997, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed a memorandum on concluding an
intergovernmental agreement on protecting and encouraging
investment. They reached an agreement on extending 800-million
U.S. dollars of loans to Russia by Japan's Export and Import Bank
as part of the 1.5-billion-dollar untied credit.
</P>
<P>
The two parties also exchanged letters on extending the 1993
agreement on peaceful space research.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin said it is important in principle that the Japanese
leadership has fully supported the Russian government's economic
stabilization course and that he is confident in Moscow's ability
to overcome the current difficulties in the country.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's visit was not affected by the political
changes in Japan, demonstrating a high degree of stability of the
Russian-Japanese relations, the Russian spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto resigned on Monday to
take responsibility for his party's setback in the upper house
election of the Japanese parliament. 
</P>
