<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Strengthen Audit Functions of Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
strengthen the auditing functions of the Philippine Central Bank
and the Deposits Insurance Corp. to make the two agencies more
effective in their role of averting bank failures and closures in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said in a news release
Wednesday that endowing more audit powers will enable the two
agencies to determine with certainty the cause of any bank failure
and the assistance and other remedial measures that must be
extended.
</P>
<P>
With more audit powers, the two agencies can immediately
recommend government takeover of banks having financial problems,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said while some small thrift and rural banks are faced
with problems, the country's banking system as a whole is stable.
</P>
<P>
On further liberalization of the banking sector by allowing
more foreign banks to enter into the country, Espiritu said the
proposals are for foreign investors to own up to 60 percent of a
bank.
</P>
<P>
The proposed 100 percent ownership of a bank by foreign
capitalists pertains to takeovers or full acquisition by foreign
banks of distressed local banks, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
