<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Budget Deficit Controlled Below Ceiling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon has successfully kept the
budget deficit below the projected yearly ceiling of 42 percent in
the first half of 1998, the Daily Star newspaper said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report by the Lebanese Finance Ministry as
saying that the deficit stood at 35 percent at the end of June,
the lowest level in five years.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the achievement mainly to the increase of
the revenues, which amounted to 1.52 billion U.S. dollars in the
first six months of 1998, rising by 27 percent from those in the
same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Spendings also decreased by 10 million dollars to 2.34 billion
dollars compared with those in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report highlighted the real estate fees collected by the
Finance Ministry, which increased by 15 percent to 81.12 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of State for Financial Affairs Fuad Sinyoura
has anticipated a further fall of the budget deficit by the end of
this year due to a drop of the interest rates of the treasury
bills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
