<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Build Four New Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will build four
new prisons throughout the country to reduce the pressure on
overcrowded prisons, the daily Star newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the new prisons is due to be accomplished
within 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The new jails, to be jointly built by the government and
private companies, would be better run at cheaper operating costs
than existing prisons in the country, Public Works Minister Jeff
Radebe was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The four jails with the cost between 200 million Rand (33
million U.S. Dollars) and 300 million Rand (50 million U.S. Dollars)
would increase the existing national capacity of jails, currently
96,000 beds, by 5300 beds.
</P>
<P>
"This (is) a completely new way of procurement and gives
effect to the government's approach of inviting private
enterprise in partnerships to deliver much-needed public
services," Radebe said.
</P>
<P>
Bert Slabber, Spokesperson for Correctional Services Minister,
said: "The private sector are more business-minded and can run
prisons more cheaply than we can."  
</P>
</TEXT>
