<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Seeking Mechanism to Implement UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian envoy to the
U.N. Nasser Kedwa said Wednesday the Palestinian National
Authority is seeking a mechanism to implement the U.N. statement
urging Israel not to expand Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian side together with the U.N. will work to find
such a mechanism," said Kedwa in a telephone interview with the
Cairo-based Voice of Arabs Radio.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council issued a presidential statement late
Monday urging Israel to rescind its Jerusalem expansion plan and
"not to take any other steps which would prejudice the outcome of
the permanent status negotiations" with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo Accord, the status of Jerusalem should be
determined in the final status talks between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
As the U.S. and Britain tried to prevent the Security Council
from voting on an Arab-sponsored resolution condemning Israel, and
the 15 council members finally adopted a watered-down presidential
statement, which is non-binding and does not carry the same weight
as a resolution.
</P>
<P>
Israel, under a storm of criticism from the international
community by approving on June 21 the controversial plan to extend
Jerusalem's boundaries to include some Jewish settlements in the
West Bank, has rejected the statement and vowed to go ahead with
the expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
If Israel fails to abide by the presidential statement, Kedwa
warned that, the council will reconsider all Israeli measures.
</P>
<P>
There is an "organic relation" between the recent U.N. decision
to upgrade the Palestinian status in the world body and the
Palestinian determination to declare an independent state in May
1999, Kedwa said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly on July 7 voted overwhelmingly to
upgrade the status of the Palestine Liberation Organization from
an observer to that of near statehood.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians has repeatedly said that an independent
Palestinian state with East Jerusalem as capital will be set up in
May 1999, regardless of the outcome of negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks have been deadlocked for 16
months over Israeli settlement construction and a long-overdue
Israeli pullout from the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review (1) China Takes Stern Measures to Rectify Banking Sector by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC),
China's central bank, is taking stern measures to put the banking
sector in good order as been evidenced by the recent closure of
the Hannan Development Bank and China Venturetech Investment Corp.
</P>
<P>
The first half of this year also saw a number of financial
institutions and dozens of individuals severely punished for
illegal banking practices.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time PBOC has shut down a commercial bank,
and it is also unprecedented that so many financial institutions
and individuals were punished in such a short time.
</P>
<P>
China's financial operations in the first half of this year
were marked by intensified rectification and the establishment of
a solid financial order, one of the key aspects of the central
bank's reforming efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Hainan Development Bank and the non-banking financial
institutions that have been shut down became insolvent due to
serious illegal operations.
</P>
<P>
Under the planned economic system, the central bank would have
done something to "rescue" them. Instead, the PBOC revoked their
licenses and allowed them to close, indicating the central bank's
determination to rectify the financial order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review (2) China Takes Stern Measures to Rectify Banking Sector by Xu Xingtang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When the State Council convened a national financial working
conference last November, the prevention of financial risk was at
the top of the country's financial reform agenda.
</P>
<P>
China has set a clear target for financial reforms: the
establishment of a modern financial system that is suited to the
socialist market economy. The essence of the reform is to push
banks into the market and have them operate in accordance with the
law governing market operations.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year all the scheduled reforms
were gradually carried out, of which rectification of the
financial order was especially emphasized.
</P>
<P>
In May the PBOC punished eight financial institutions in
Yunnan, Anhui, Henan, Hubei and other provinces for their
malpractices. Thereafter, more financial institutions and
individuals involved in illegal operations received severe
punishment.
</P>
<P>
The PBOC has also initiated pilot projects in some
provinces to restructure rural credit cooperatives in a bid to
ward off financial risk in these cooperatives.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China is improving its legal environment for
the rectification of the financial order. Following the
regulations on the punishment of people involved in financial
malpractices issued by the PBOC in June, new procedures on closing
illegal financial institutions and illegal financial operations
were adopted by the State Council on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Related sources say that in order to tighten supervision over
financial institutions, financial authorities are formulating a
series of programs for rectifying the financial order and
preventing financial risk.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Compromise Talks Yet with Marcoses: Estrada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Wednesday emphasized that the government has not yet entered into
any negotiations with the Marcoses concerning the settlement of
the ill-gotten wealth cases against them.
</P>
<P>
Estrada assured the public in a statement that his
administration will remain transparent on the issue, and will
immediately inform the public of any development on a possible
compromise settlement.
</P>
<P>
"If an out-of-court settlement is forged then the Filipino
people will know about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said his administration has already suffered a barrage of
criticism from several sectors on the issue although the
Presidential Commission on Good Government has not yet even talked
directly to the Marcoses.
</P>
<P>
Estrada noted that his predecessors, former presidents Fidel
Ramos and Corazon Aquino, initiated out-of-court settlements with
relatives and close associates of the late president Marcos
without any strong opposition from the public.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Estrada announced he will seek the advice of
Congress on any proposed compromise settlement between the
government and the Marcoses.
</P>
<P>
Estrada had said his administration is ready to enter into a
compromise agreement with the Marcoses over the ill-gotten wealth
suits so the money could be used to uplift the living standard of
the poor.
</P>
<P>
He said the cash-strapped government could use the money from
the compromise deal to bankroll mass housing projects, livelihood
and job-generation programs and agricultural reforms to ensure
food security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
