<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2002 World Cup Hosts Push Ahead with Stadium Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Japan and South Korea, co-hosts of
the 2002 World Cup, are pushing ahead with their plans to build
new stadiums in spite of the economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
According to the plans, each country has already identified 10
host venues.
</P>
<P>
Japan has completed two stadiums, Yokohama and Osaka and will
build other venues include Kobe, Ibaraki, Miyagi, Niigata, Oita,
Saitama, Sapporo and Shizuoka.
</P>
<P>
While venues in three South Korean cities, Pusan, Taegu and
Inchon, are under now construction.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government will provide 30 percent of the
costs of building each of the 10 stadiums.
</P>
<P>
The construction of nine of the stadiums in Japan will be
completed by the spring of 2001 with the last one in the city of
Kobe set to be finished by the autumn.
</P>
<P>
With 64 matches taking place in the 2002 World Cup finals, each
of the 20 stadiums selected by the two countries could be expected
to hold only three matches.
</P>
<P>
The opening game will be held in Seoul along with the third
place play-off if FIFA does not scrap that match.
</P>
<P>
The World Cup final will be staged in Japan at either the newly
constructed 70,000-seat Yokohama International Stadium or the
63,000-seat Saitama Prefectural Stadium.
</P>
<P>
A decision on which venue will host the final will be taken
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
