<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interbank Commercial Rates Continue Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The interbank commercial rates
registered a decline in the week to last Friday in the domestic
money market, as activity at the Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE)
continued to be depressed.
</P>
<P>
The average interbank rate fell to 16.87 percent, compared to
20.66 percent and 29.10 percent in the previous two weeks,
according to the latest issue of the Central Bank's weekly market
bulletin.
</P>
<P>
In the money marketh`0nterest on the 91-day treasury bill
maintained its declining trend, with the rates falling to 24.74
percent in the auction dated July 13 from 24.92 percent in the
previous auction.
</P>
<P>
During the week, commercial banks' base lending rates fell
marginally from 27.80 percent to 27.78 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mashreq Bank and Habib Bank Ltd. continued to give the lowest
base lending rate of 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
Coop Merchant Bank, Barclays Bank of Kenya and National Bank
had their base lending rate reduced to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Euro Bank, Biashara Bank, Guilders and Commerce Bank offered
the highest base lending rate of 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the CBK chief economist Maurice Kanga said
that the country had experienced only 1.9 percent growth in the
past 12 months to March 1998.
</P>
<P>
Given the economic situation that befell the country, the
performance was impressive, Kanga said.
</P>
<P>
On equities, 313,000 shares were traded at the NSE Tuesday,
down from Monday's 456,000.
</P>
<P>
The trend at the market has generally been depressed for
several months now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
