<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Warned Against Targeting UN Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations peacekeeping
force in south Lebanon has issued a strong warning to Israeli army
against targeting the peacekeepers, the Daily Star reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a strong-worded statement, the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon
(UNIFIL) said it was unacceptable to target UNIFIL troops and
Israeli troops should avoid the repetition of such mistakes, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, an Irish soldier of the UNIFIL and a Lebanese
civilian were wounded when Israeli mortar shells hit a UNIFIL jeep
in the Hataida village in the central sector of Israeli-occupied
zone.
</P>
<P>
The village is believed to be a hideout for the Iranian-backed
anti-Israeli guerrilla group Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Monday raid came shortly after its post in Sojud in
the eastern sector of the zone was attacked by the guerrilla group.
</P>
<P>
The Irish soldier is the first U.N. peacekeeper wounded in
south Lebanon so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Since the UNIFIL was established in 1978 after Israel's first
invasion of Lebanon, 222 peacekeepers have died in separate
incidents, 38 of them were Irish soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-member UNIFIL was deployed to restore peace and
security across the border between Israel and Lebanon, and observe
the Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has long complained that the U.N. troops have been
ineffective in protecting its northern areas from Lebanese
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel occupied a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon in 1985, Lebanese resistance groups spearheaded by
the Hezbollah have been fighting to oust the Israeli occupation
troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
