<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise for 3rd Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices surged in Tokyo for the
third consecutive trading day Wednesday, boosted by active stock
purchases by foreign brokerages.
</P>
<P>
But renewed fears over Japan's feeble banking system prevented
the key Nikkei index from posting strong gains.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 125.23 points, or 0.76
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 16,614.14.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 8.66 points or 0.68 percent to
1,275.31.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 450
million shares from Tuesday's 402.08 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel, attractive to some because of its relatively low
share price and outstanding liquidity, was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Healthy stock purchases by foreign brokerages and the record
high seen in the Dow Jones Industrial Average overnight in New
York buoyed market sentiment, traders said.
</P>
<P>
But stocks struggled to advance further as institutional
investors quickly sold off shares to seek out better buys.
</P>
<P>
Also dragging on share prices was the fall of many bank stocks
in reaction to market rumors that Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
(LTCB) and Sumitomo Trust and Banking had given up on a possible
merger, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
outnumbered losers 635 to 497, with 142 issues finishing
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
