<HEADLINE> Censure Motion Against Turkish PM Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Parliament decided late
Tuesday night to put a censure motion against Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz on its agenda, the Milliyet daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The motion, submitted by the opposition Virtue Party (FP), was
approved by 225-213.
</P>
<P>
The motion charged that Yilmaz had illegally assigned a plot of
land belonging to the state-owned paper and pulp company SEKA in
Izmit, near Istanbul, to the industrialist giant Koc Group.
</P>
<P>
The FP, True Path Party (DYP), National Movement Party and
some other political parties supported the motion.
</P>
<P>
A parliamentary hearing will be held within seven days
according to the law, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
On April 22, the Turkish parliament decided to investigate the
allegations that Yilmaz had omitted some shares in Turkey's
Finance Bank between 1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the inquiry into Yilmaz's private wealth
was a retaliation launched by the DYP for a probe into its leader
Tansu Ciller's private property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
