<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Weapon Allowed in 1999 South African Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will impose a
general ban on the carrying of weapons at political meetings or
any other political events during the 1999 general election
campaign, local daily the Citizen reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Once a state of election is declared, "no person may carry or
display arms or weapons at a political meeting, march,
demonstration, rally or other public political event".
</P>
<P>
This is one of the provisions of a code of conduct, which is
set out in the Electoral Bill, introduced in parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Political parties and their candidates will be liable to a
fine of 200,000 Rand (about 33,000 U.S. Dollars) or being barred
from contesting next year's general elections if they infringe
the code of conduct or the laws contained in the bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill, introduced by Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, will be approved soon after parliament resumes next
week, in order to set up the official machinery for the 1999
general elections, parliament sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
