<HEADLINE> S. Africa's New Labor Minister Calls for Creating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's new Labor
Minister Shepherd Mdladlana has described job creation as one of
his priorities and called on South Africans from all walks of
life to support the government efforts for creating more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Mdladlana was sworn in Tuesday in Pretoria, local media
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The labor minister said that job creation would be one of his
immediate priorities as the government prepares for the
presidential job summit scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
Mdladlana was former president of the South Africa Democratic
Teachers' Union and was principal of a primary school in Cape
Town before he became a parliament member in 1994.
</P>
<P>
He stepped in after former labor minister Tito Mboweni was
appointed Reserve Bank's governor last week and began his
one-year internship under Governor Chris Stals.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni's appointment sparked criticism from opposition
parties, which feared that the move might endanger the
independence of the central bank.  
