<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Kill 12 People in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 12 people were killed in
Bangladesh on Tuesday as floods inundated more areas and rendered
more people homeless, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Four people were drowned in flood waters in northwestern
Jamalpur district, where at least another 100 villages went under
water and some 20 educational institutions closed due to flooding.
</P>
<P>
Another three persons were killed in landslides due to heavy
downpour in Rangamati Hill district, and a one-year-old boy also
died in a landslide in the off-shore island of Moheshkhali under
Cox's Bazar district, southeast Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
And in Bogra district, about 170 kilometers northwest of here,
three boys and one girl were drowned.
</P>
<P>
Over 600,000 more people were affected by the floods, and huge
tracts of standing crops were washed away on Tuesday, officials
were quoted by the press reports as saying.
</P>
<P>
Heavy floods disrupted traffic in many parts of the country,
according to the reports. Traffic on the Dhaka-Chittagon highway
was cut off for several hours Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, prices of daily necessities went up, exacerbating
miseries of the common people, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on Tuesday expressed her deep
concern over the plight of the food-hit people and directed
district administrations to take all necessary measures to
mitigate their sufferings.
</P>
<P>
The directives issued by the Prime Minister's Office said that
district administrations should identify the flood-prone areas and
work out necessary preparedness plans for evacuating the
flood-affected people and undertaking relief operations in the
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
She asked the local administrations to work out post-flood
rehabilitation programs and to integrate the local people and
social and voluntary organizations in combating the natural
calamity.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million people have been affected and over 1
million acres of crops damaged by floods in Bangladesh since the
monsoon season began in July.
</P>
<P>
There are frequent heavy rains in the monsoon season (from July
to October) in the South Asian nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
