<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Live Fish Discovered in Taklamakan Desert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist has disovered a
living fish in the central part of the Taklamakan desert in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yiyu, vice-president of Chinese Academy of Sciences,
China's top scientific research institute, discovered the fish
swimming happyly in a water pit near No.4 Tazhong Oilfield in the
desert.
</P>
<P>
He was there on a field investigation for planting more trees
in the oilfields there.
</P>
<P>
Taklamakan suffers from serious drought and is generally
believed to be a place where aquatic life cannot survive.
</P>
<P>
The black fish is about a thumb's length and pencil thin.
</P>
<P>
Chen has ruled out the possibility that the fish was brought to
the desert for breeding by people working there.
</P>
<P>
Chen, authority on aquatic animals, said the fish is a kind of
freshwater fish and has already adapted itself to the slightly
salty water.
</P>
<P>
Chen said workers in the desert use bulldozers in highway
construction and many pits are carved out by the digging, and
some of the pits then fill with ground water.
</P>
<P>
Though the temperature is often as high as 40 degrees centigrade
in summer, the water in the pit often remains because of the
constant addition of ground water.
</P>
<P>
The oil workers have built a 522-kilometer long highway across
the desert.
</P>
<P>
With the help of scientists from the CAS, 13 hectares of desert
plants have been planted along the highway along with housing for
the workers.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have since brought the fish to Beijing for further
research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
