<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Capital Turning Into Modern Commercial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Xi'an, famous as one of the world's
four major ancient capitals along with Athens, Cairo and Rome, is
fast becoming a modern commercial center in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
By financial restructuring and opening up to the outside world,
this capital city of northwest China's Shaanxi Province has set up
a new commercial system of varied forms of ownership and established
direct economic and trade ties with more than 100 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, some comparatively large state-owned
commercial firms have been merged into eight groups, four of which
have been listed on the stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Over 93 percent of the local small shops also have introduced
various types of ownership. As a result, 90 percent of money-losing
businesses have reduced losses or became profitable.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an has also spent about 4.6 billion yuan on construction of
commercial facilities in the last five years. At present, the city
has 20 large and medium-sized department stores and 500-odd small
markets.
</P>
<P>
Improved facilities and investment environment have attracted
over 20 commercial firms from the United States, Japan, Italy and
Germany for establishing joint ventures or trade links with Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an was the starting point of the ancient Silk Road, the
route over which China's silk, tea and compasses, as well as the
expertise needed to make paper, gunpowder and herbal medicines
were exported to West Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
In 221 B.C., the Qin Dynasty, China's first feudal dynasty,
made the city its capital. During the Tang Dynasty (618-907),
Xi'an was the largest international metropolis in the world and
home to a population of one million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
