<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ, Australia Both Claim Seabed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand and Australia are
each laying claim to the same piece of continental shelf seabed.
</P>
<P>
According to today's local newspaper the Evening Post, the
claimed area includes seabed between the North Island of New
Zealand and Lord Howe Island, an Australian-owned island off the
coast of New South Wales.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's Foreign Affairs and Trade spokesman James Funnell
was quoted as saying that a "long, drawn out process" was involved
before anything was decided. Four joint surveys have been carried
out to determine continental shelf boundaries between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Because the continental shelf is part of the land mass, it
becomes claimable territory, Funnell said.
</P>
<P>
"We are or have been doing joint seabed surveys with the
Australians," he said. "And we are both going off and doing our
own interpretation of data and then we are going to get together.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, there are a couple of areas of seabed outside both
countries' 200-mile economic zones that we both have an interest
in. What we are trying to do by doing this survey work is to reach
some points of agreement on what we lay claim to," Funnell said,
adding "No one is on the verge of doing anything. We're just very
carefully working through the data from the surveys and then we're
talking. It's quite a long, drawn out process."
</P>
<P>
Funnell said that the main reason for extending seabed
jurisdiction was for exploration purposes. A successful claim will
give New Zealand exploration rights, such as rights to drill for
oil and gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
