<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 07:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Investors Demand Lowering Israeli Input </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian investors at a major
Jordanian-Israeli industrial zone has shunned the duty-free
treatment provided by the U.S. due to their demand for lowering
the percentage of the Israeli input.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal signed between Israel and Jordan last November,
products manufactured in the Qualifying Industrial Zone (QIZ) in
Irbid, some 80 kilometers north to Amman, could be exported to the
U.S. duty-free on condition that they include at least 11.7
percent of Israeli input.
</P>
<P>
Saying the percentage of Israeli input was too high, Jordanian
investors have rejected the beneficial U.S. treatment provided as
a reaward for the kingdom's contribution to the Middle East peace
process, the semi-official Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. trade department has been surprised that since the
QIZ was officially designated in March, nobody has applied for a
duty-free entry into the U.S.," the paper quoted Omar Salah,
Chairman of the Century Investment Group, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian investors will not apply for a duty-free status
for their products destined for the U.S. markets before Israel
agrees to lower the percentage to give more profits away to the
Jordanians, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
"The 11.7 percent input from Israel is too high. We are
working now on lowering it to 3 percent," said Salah, who opens
eight factories at the zone.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the Israelis are showing some flexibility and
the problem could be resolved by October when a U.S. official from
the Department of Commerce visits the region.
</P>
<P>
If Israel agrees on a 3 percent input, Jordan will have to
either increase its present 11.7 percent contribution or
introduce a 10 percent U.S. input as stipulated in the deal, Salah
added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., as the leading sponsor of the peace process, strongly
supports the QIZ deal which was designed to bring economic
dividends to Jordan which sealed peace with Israel in 1994.
</P>
<P>
For Jordan, the QIZ deal means new markets and it has created
over 2,000 job opportunities for its growing unemployed
population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
