<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Improving Environmental Protection In Eastern Chinese Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 small companies
that are serious polluters in the Taihu Lake valley in east
China's Zhejiang Province have been closed down as part of the
province's efforts to halt the degradation by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Taihu is in the Yangtze River Delta and is one of China's major
fresh water lakes. About a third of it is in Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The polluters have spent about 200 million yuan (25 million
U.S. dollars) on pollution controls and 90 percent have pollution
treatment facilities, according to the provincial environmental
protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
This year, the province has decided that no work units in the
Taihu Lake valley which fail to meet pollution control standards
can let their waste waster flow into the lake after January 1,
1999.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has recently worked out preferential
policies for key enterprises for waste treatment and loans of no
less than 30 million yuan for water treatment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
