<HEADLINE> Senior Judge Gets Prison Sentence For Accepting Bribes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese judge who was
found guilty of accepting bribes has been sentenced to 15 years in
prison, the Supreme People's Court announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Pan Yile, 58, vice-president of the Higher People's Court of
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, was found guilty of
accepting 250,000 yuan (30,000 U.S. dollars) worth of bribes, the
SPC says.
</P>
<P>
The case involved a man named Gao who owned an auction house in
Guangxi and got to know Pan when he filed two lawsuits with Pan's
higher court in 1995. In 1996, the senior judge accepted 10
percent of Gao's new gold mining company shares, worth 250,000
yuan, and was made vice-chairman of board of directors of the
company.
</P>
<P>
Pan later forged documents to cover up the bribe.
</P>
<P>
The case against Pan was handed over to Beijing No.1
Intermediate People's Court because of his position as a higher
court vice-president.
</P>
<P>
According to the SPC, the case was first reported by
individuals, and the Supreme People's Court gave it a great deal
of attention and sent people to investigate.
</P>
<P>
After the first judgement was handed down, Pan appealed to the
Beijing Higher People's Court, which found the verdict in line
with the facts of the case and upheld it.
</P>
<P>
An SPC official has said that making such a high-profile case
open during this period of judicial reforms shows the judiciary's
determination to crack down on corruption and to see that justice
is served.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
