<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Goodwill Games to Open Saturday in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The 1998 Goodwill Games, an
international multi-sport invitational uniting the world's best
athletes, will be staged in New York, the United States, from July
19 to August 2.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 athletes from more than 60 countries will compete
in 15 sports including athletics, basketball, boxing, track
cycling, diving, figure skating, gymnastics, rhythmic gymnastics,
soccer, swimming, synchronized swimming, triathlon, beach
volleyball, water polo, wrestling.
</P>
<P>
A total of five million U.S. dollars in prize money and record
incentives will be awarded, creating the largest purse in
multi-sport event history.
</P>
<P>
The world's elite international athletes and teams are invited
to participate based on their international standings and
performances at major international competitions.
</P>
<P>
The Games have their signature, "finals-only" format for
individual events, which means there are no preliminaries or
qualification heats. Champions in the team events and boxing are
determined through elimination rounds, culminating in a gold-medal
match.
</P>
<P>
All venues will be located in Manhattan, Nassau County and
Staten Island. The New York state and Nassau county government are
covering the costs for the new multi-million dollar Nassau County
Goodwill Games Aquatics Center and the 22 million U.S. dollars
renovation of the Nassau County Mitchel Athletics Complex,
respectively. Both are located on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
It will be the fourth edition of the Goodwill Games, which was
first held in Moscow in 1986. It was the brainchild of Ted Turner,
President of the Turner Broadcasting System, who created it in
response to the U.S. absence from the 1980 Moscow Olympics and
Soviet boycott the 1984 Los Angeles Olympics. The Games aimed at
bringing the world's best athletes an additional opportunity to
compete in a major international forum.
</P>
<P>
Beginning in 1998, goodwill has been redefined for the Goodwill
Games. The Games have adopted a new cause "benefiting
children". The Goodwill Games official charities are the Boys &AMP;
Girls Clubs of America and UNICEF International. The Games have
teamed up with TBS Superstation for the million dollar
SuperChallenge.
</P>
<P>
The SuperChallenge is a fund-matching program which aims to
generate one million hours of volunteer time and one million
U.S. dollars for the national organization of the Boys &AMP; Girls
Clubs of America. Time Warner is making a donation to UNICEF
International on behalf of the Games.
</P>
<P>
The previous three Games were held in Moscow in 1986, Seattle,
Washington, in 1990, and St. Petersbury, Russia in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Best Swimmers to Compete in Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A unique team format, along
with one of the largest prize purses in swimming's history, will
added to the action as the world's top swimmers compete in the
Goodwill Games starting on Saturday in Nassau County of New York,
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We anticipated records will be broken in this sensational
aquatics event," said Goodwill Games President Mike Plant
recently. "With the caliber of athletes, the unique team format
and this new facility, spectators and viewers will experience an
unforgettable and highly competitive swimming competition."
</P>
<P>
The swimming and diving events will be held at the brand new
Nassau County Goodwill Games swimming and diving center. The
competition will feature a total of eight teams, four women's and
four men's. The teams competing in the women's pool are China, the
United States, Germany and a world all-star team. Men's team
competing are the United States, Russia, Germany and a world
all-star team.
</P>
<P>
The unique swimming format will feature teams competing
head-to-head in a round-robin dual meet format (50-meter course)
consisting of 14 events.
</P>
<P>
The order of events within each meet is as follows: 400m medley
relay, 800m freestyle, 200m freestyle, 100m backstroke, 50m
freestyle, 100m breaststroke, 200m butterfly, 100m freestyle, 200m
backstroke, 200m breaststroke, 400m freestyle, 100m butterfly,
200m individual medley, 400m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Each team will compete and be scored in three dual meets. Final
team placements will be determined by team results at the end of
competition. Individuals will also be scored on best performances
in each individual event.
</P>
<P>
The Games' swimming competition will feature many of the
world's top swimmers. Expected on the Russian team are Olympic
champions Aleksandr Popov and Denis Pankratov. On the world
all-star team are Brazil's Gustavo Borges, South Africa's Penny
Heyns, Netherland's Marcel Wouda, Coasta Rica's Claudia Poll, and
additional athletes from Belgium, Italy, Japan and other countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. team will showcase an amazing array of talent
including six world champions and 11 Olympic gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
The Goodwill Games will award teams and individuals with one of
the largest prize purses ever in a swimming competition. Prize
money structure for teams is the following: first - $50,000,
second - $25,000, third - $15,000 and fourth - $10,000.
Individuals turning in the fastest times for each event will be
awarded $1,000. An additional $50,000 bonus will be awarded for
setting up world records during the Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
