<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Police Tracing 57,353 Stolen Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian police are tracing a total
of 57,353 cars stolen by international theft gangs, a report said
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Lyubomir Yossifov of the Police National
Service Directorate as saying that of those on the list, 11,847
are being sought at INTERPOL's request.
</P>
<P>
Among the 57,353 missing vehicles, 16,134 are Ladas followed by
6,455 Volkswagens, 6,379 Mercedeses, 4,106 Fiats, 3,876 Fords,
3,335 BMWs, Yossifov said.
</P>
<P>
The number of the stolen Opels, Audis, Moskoviches, Peugeots
and Renaults is less than 3,000, he added.
</P>
<P>
Missing car reports arrive almost daily from the INTERPOL
National Bureau, he said. Between January 1 and July 10 this year,
5,394 vehicles were put on the list.
</P>
<P>
In Bulgaria, criminal groups steal mainly expensive automobiles
or parts, which are often trafficked to Macedonia, Albania,
Moldova, Ukraine and Russia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Larger gangs smuggled stolen cars from Western Europe and
redistributed them to the former Soviet republics and to the Arab
world via Bulgaria and Turkey, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 70 percent of the stolen cars which had passed through or
been sold in Bulgaria came from Western Europe, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some Bulgarian customs officers are on record for involvement
in such smuggling, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Jute Production to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Jute production is expected to
decline in Bangladesh this year as farmers have lost their
interest to cultivate the cash crop due to low prices of raw jute
and jute goods both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
The area for jute growing in the 1988-99 fiscal year beginning
July 1 has decreased to 1.2 million acres with an output target of
4.5 million bales (0.81 million tons), after a bumper crop of 6.5
million bales (1.17 million tons) on 1.6 million acres of land
during the past fiscal, according to a survey of the Agricultural
Extension Directorate available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jute experts, however, estimated that the production would not
exceed 3 million bales (0.54 million tons) and not more than
900,000 acres of land would be brought under jute cultivation
during the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The average price of jute at the growers level has decreased
dramatically during the past two years, from 506 taka (10.77 U.S.
dollars) per maund (37.36 kilograms) in July 1996 to 373 taka
(7.94 dollars) in December the same year, and from 229 taka (4.87
dollars) per maund in July 1997 to 197 taka (4.19 dollars) in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh earned 434.2 million U.S. dollars during the 1996-97
fiscal year from its jute industry, one of the country's major
foreign exchange earners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Audit Shows Poor Accounting of U.S Drug-Fighting Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- An audit has shown that the
Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) has kept sloppy records and
could not account for money and drugs seized in drugs operations.
</P>
<P>
The audit concluded that the main U.S. drug fighter has not
been able to "accurately and completely account" for the property
it owned, the money that drug traffickers give undercover agents
during sting operations or the seized drugs it has on hand.
</P>
<P>
The DEA's accounting was so poor in 1997 that the private
accounting firm which conducted the audit under new government
accountability laws said it could not form an opinion as to
whether the agency's books were accurate.
</P>
<P>
"We were unable to satisfy ourselves as to the fair
presentation of these balances and transactions," Peat Marwick
reported after looking at DEA's 1997 books.
</P>
<P>
The audit cited DEA for several "material weaknesses", the most
severe criticism in professional accounting. Some of the concerns
had been brought to the agency's attention in previous years.
</P>
<P>
The agency agreed with the findings. The Justice Department,
which oversees the DEA, said Tuesday that while it hasn't seen the
final audit it is aware of the concerns and believes they have
been adequately addressed with a new accounting system DEA is
implementing this year.
</P>
<P>
"The department is committed to addressing the problems that
have been raised," said Chris Watney, a Justice Department
spokeswoman. "The department acknowledges there were concerns
about DEA's antiquated financial system, and a new more modern
system is being implemented now that addresses those concerns. The
attorney general had made it a high priority to see those changes
through."
</P>
<P>
A DEA official said Tuesday that all of the recommendations in
the audit are being implemented.
</P>
<P>
The Senate Judiciary Committee is expected to quiz Attorney
General Janet Reno about the problem at a hearing Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
