<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Criticizes U.S. for Lack Support for ICC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 14 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan has criticized the United States and nine other countries
for their lack of support in the creation of the International
Criminal Court (ICC).
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.S. secretary of state, Madeleine Albright,
and nine of her colleagues on Saturday, and released yesterday
evening in New York, Annan claimed that some delegations to the
ICC conference, including Albright's, "do not seem ready to find
an agreement with the others".
</P>
<P>
The UN conference on the establishment of an ICC, is being held
in Rome. The outcome is now in doubt, partly because of
U.S. pressure against UN plans to set up the ICC to try war
crimes and crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
The conference is scheduled to end on Friday with a final draft
of the court's statute to be signed during a special ceremony on
Saturday in Rome.
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian media, the U.S., France, Syria and
India are the main sources of opposition to the many countries who
favor giving court prosecutors the right to pursue cases of
genocide, war crimes or crimes against humanity " without asking
for the permission of the relative countries or the UN Security
Council".
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the conference's plenary assembly, Philippe
Krish of Canada said: "I hope the U.S. will be part of the statute
marking the court's creation. What we want is a strong statute
signed by the largest number of countries possible."
</P>
<P>
The ICC is designed to be an international criminal tribunal
where defendants will be individuals, whereas the existing
International Court of Justice at the Hague settles judicial
controversies between sovereign states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
