<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovak Republic Issues Bonds to Raise Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Slovak
Republic issued 2.11 billion Koruny (68 million U.S.dollars) of
bonds on July 14 to ease its financial stress.
</P>
<P>
The total value of the issued bonds this year is greater than
usual. The bonds have an annual interest rate of 19.8 percent with
a one-year maturity term, a government official said..
</P>
<P>
The government had to issue bonds in recent years to raise
funds as the country has been plagued with increasing financial
deficit.
</P>
<P>
The Slovak Republic had registered a deficit of 37 billion
Koruny (1.2 billion dollars) last year. The deficit has reached
3.9 billion Koruny (122 million dollars) in the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Since its independence in 1993, the government has issued bonds
for several times. In 1996 and 1997, it issued bonds worth 53.7
billion Koruny (1.7 billion dollars) and 61.5 billion Koruny (1.9
billion dollars), respectively. The amount has hit 66.9 billion
Koruny (2.1 billion dollars) in the first three months of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
