<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Coal-Rich Shanxi Hopes to Become Large Power Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province will
build or expand ten large power plants at a cost of 70 billion
yuan over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The province hopes to increase power generating capacity by
830,000 kw annually through the next two years' construction,
according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
The plan is viewed as a way to spur the slow pace of economic
development in Shanxi where the demand for general manufactured
goods has remained sluggish, and the coal market has been weak
since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi now has a power generating capacity of 10 million kw and
is capable of producing 54.5 billion kw/hours of electricity
annually. Each year, it sells 10 billion kw/hours of electricity
to supply customers outside of Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
By year 2000, the province's total power generating capacity
will be 13.42 million kw, of which four million kw will be for
customers outside Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi, dubbed the "sea of coal", has a verified coal reserve
of 287.3 billion tons, accounting for one-third of China's total
and ranking first in the country. It produces 300 million tons of
coal annually, one-quarter of China's total coal production.
</P>
<P>
Construction of several pit thermal power plants alongside the
existing coal mines, and trans-regional long-distance power
transmission lines are now under construction.
</P>
<P>
When all the large thermal power stations are completed, 50
million tons of coal will be transformed into electricity annually
near their production sites. This will also contribute to
alleviating the pressure on railway transport for shipping coal
out of Shanxi, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, electricity was available in 97.8
percent of Shanxi Province's villages and will be extended to all
villages by the end of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
