<HEADLINE> Thailand Asks U.S. to Buy Back F/A-18 Spare Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Air Force is to ask the
United States to buy back spare parts of the F/A-18 fighter
planes, the purchase contract of which was terminated halfway
through due to insufficient funds, the Bangkok Post reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The parts, worth about 30 million U.S. dollars, are no longer
of use since the Thai Air Force cannot afford the U.S.-made
planes.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had taken back the jets without imposing fines on the
Thai government for abandoning the purchase. But it did not return
the 74.5-million-U.S.-dollar deposit the Thai Air Force placed for
ordering the jets.
</P>
<P>
A Thai Armed Forces delegation headed by Supreme Commander
General Mongkol Ampornpisit will visit the United States to
negotiate the spare parts deal.
</P>
<P>
Mongkol was quoted as saying that his visit would touch on
security matters and is aimed at strengthening the military ties
with Washington. The discussion of the spare parts sale was also
high on the agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
