<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Countries Agree to Boost Information Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Information ministers of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) have agreed to
launch an ASEAN satellite channel by 2000 as a step to enhance
exchange of information.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the just-concluded fifth biennial
meeting of ASEAN information ministers, conference sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed to launch a new website for culture
and information, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Supatra Masdit, minister of Thailand's Prime Minister's Office,
said at the two-day meeting that Thailand would take the first
step to help boost the information exchange among ASEAN member
states.
</P>
<P>
He said Channel 5 of Thailand, which is already beaming all
over the world, would be able to show the way for other ASEAN
member states in receiving from and transmitting to the ASEAN
channel.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN television channel is set to reach all member
countries before extending to the rest of the world. ASEAN groups
Myanmar, Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Cambodia, a prospective member,
attended the meeting as an observer.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's Minister of Information George Yeo indicated the
group's support for Malaysia's cost-saving proposal for national
channels to beam to an existing satellite rather than launching a
new one.
</P>
<P>
National channels would only have to pay the cost of renting
separate transpondents, Yeo said.
</P>
<P>
Singapore is to host a meeting in October to settle funding
arrangements and appoint a network coordinator.
</P>
<P>
But Yeo stressed that the new website and planned satellite
channel were efforts by ASEAN to "make our gentle voices from the
region to be heard", not to counter Western mass media.
</P>
<P>
U Kyaw Min, editor of Myanmar's official newspaper New Light of
Myanmar, said Rangoon might be selective about presenting
information from the ASEAN channel to Myanmar viewers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
