<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Students Arrested for Ragging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Five senior students of Sri
Lanka's Royal College in Polonnaruwa in the North Central Province
were arrested by the police in connection with an alleged ragging
incident at the school Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Five new students to the school were severely ragged by the
seniors and police had to intervene to free the new students.
</P>
<P>
One student had to be admitted to hospital as a result of
injuries received during the ragging, reports reaching here said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka recently introduced anti-ragging laws following the
death of three students at different educational institutions
after incidents of ragging.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Richard Pathirana has ordered the full force
of the new laws to be taken against the students of Royal College
in Polonnaruwa, according to the ministry sources Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A special team from the Education Ministry will leave for
Polonnaruwa Wednesday to conduct a full investigation at the
instruction of the minister.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the arrested students will not be allowed to sit
for public examinations in August and they are liable to a jail
sentence if found guilty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
