<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Listed Companies Suffer Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 166 of Indonesia's 289
listed companies toppled into the red last year due to massive
foreign exchange losses.
</P>
<P>
They suffered total foreign exchange losses of 18.6 trillion
rupiah (4 billion U.S. dollars) in December last year, the
Indonesian Business Data Center (PDBI) said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange losses would be even larger if overseas debts
were calculated at the June exchange rate level of about 15,000
rupiah to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah, which was around 2,450 to the dollar in July last
year, has since lost about 80 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
"This is a time bomb and bad news for stock investors," said
PDBI's chief research officer Beni Sindhunata.
</P>
<P>
PDBI concluded that the sharp depreciation of the rupiah had
rendered the country's listed companies cheap because the total
equity of 91 trillion was only valued at 6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This is an opportunity for foreign investors to acquire
Indonesian companies at bargain levels," Beni said, adding that
local companies could form partnerships with foreign strategic
partners to survive the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
