<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Succeed in Growing Wheat in Frigid Northeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 15 (Xinhua) --Chinese scientists have been
successful in growing 13,333 hectares of winter wheat in frigid
northeastern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
This has added 50 million kg of winter wheat to the region,
said Hou Libai, an associate professor at Shenyang Agricultural
University in Liaoning Province. The winter wheat can resist the
cold to as low as minus 28 degrees Celsius. It has been used in
more than 70 counties and cities in northeast China since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hou is a member of a research team that has transferred winter
wheat from its traditional home, south of the Great Wall to
northern parts of China. Average output per mu (0.067 hectares) in
the Northeast is 350 kg, 30 percent more than spring wheat in the
same region.
</P>
<P>
Hou says that about 2.67 million hectares of farmland are
suited to winter wheat in the Northeast, and researchers claim
that 12 billion kg of wheat can be produced if winter wheat
strains are used.
</P>
<P>
Winter wheat was not used in the Northeast for a long time
because of the frigid weather and spring wheat, whose quality and
output is not as high, was more common.
</P>
<P>
Before the introduction of winter wheat, Liaoning, Jilin, and
Heilongjiang provinces and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region
had to import about 5 billion kg of wheat annually.
</P>
<P>
Hou began cooperating with researchers from the Chinese Academy
of Agricultural Sciences' Crops Institute in 1991 to study the use
of winter wheat in the frigid Northeast. They tried two
cold-resistant strains in four counties of Liaoning Province, with
per mu output reaching 326 kg, twice the output of spring wheat
there.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0268 </DOCNO>
