<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Targets 2.5 Percent Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
decided to maintain the 2.5 percent gross national product (GNP)
growth target for this year despite the lingering financial and
currency crisis and the government's deteriorating fiscal
position.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said the target, which is
already a downward revision from the original growth forecast of
between 3 and 4 percent, can still be realized, the Business Daily
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have established that the 2.5 percent GNP growth is still
attainable. But to do this, we have to work toward reducing the
budget deficit," Espiritu disclosed in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He added that a balanced budget was no longer attainable but
that the administration was pursuing measures to check the ever
increasing budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
He said the deficit was expected to hit 70 billion pesos (1.7
billion U.S. dollars) should moves to check the development fail.
</P>
<P>
The country's cash budget deficit increased dramatically from
15.4 billion pesos (375.6 million dollars) last May to 26.7
billion pesos (651.2 million dollars) for the month of June.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu reiterated that by reducing the spending gap, a cap
could be put on the country's inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Should all measures fail, he said, the country's lone recourse
would be to turn to foreign borrowings available from the World
Bank, Asian Development Bank and other multilateral institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
