<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Governmental Science &AMP; Tech Business Booms in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, north China's largest
port city, now has nearly 5,000 non-governmental enterprises
engaged in science and technology, and this sector is expected to
become a new force for local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
During the first five months this year, these enterprises
received 7.05 billion yuan (850 million US dollars) in returns
from technology, industry and trade, a 31.2 percent rise from the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The speedy development of local non-governmental science and
technology businesses, which emerged in the 1980's, has greatly
enhanced the strength of the local scientific and technological
sector.
</P>
<P>
The non-governmental enterprises do business in various areas
including on chemicals, electronic telecom, machinery, instruments
and meters, computers and networks, building materials,
pharmaceuticals, and environment-friendly technology.
</P>
<P>
Some of these enterprises have become hi-tech group companies
with an annual output value of more than 100 million yuan (12
million US dollars), allowing them to compete in international
markets.
</P>
<P>
These businesses employ in excess of 120,000 people, 45 percent
of whom are scientific and technological personnel, nine percent
higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 laid-off workers from local state-owned
enterprises now have been reemployeed in these non-governmental
businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
