<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Longest Bamboo Belt Being Built Along Hongshui River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China is building a
479-kilometer-long protective bamboo belt along the Hongshui River
in south China as part of its efforts to control soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
This barrier, believed to be the longest in the country, is
being built to a width of 40 meters along the banks of the
river. The project is expected to be completed in two years.
</P>
<P>
With an abundant flow of water, the 1,050-kilometer-long
Hongshui River is one of the ten major hydro-electric power bases
in China. However, soil erosion is a serious problem along the
river. The protective belt is being launched in a section of the
river in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that a total of 10,000 hectares of bamboo will
be planted in the belt, and they are expected to grow ripe in four
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
