<HEADLINE> Thai, Cambodian Navies Agree on Joint Patrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Thai and Cambodian navies will
begin a joint operation to patrol common territorial waters to
tackle maritime crimes and intrusion problems.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reached at a weekend border meeting between
Vice Admiral Wasin Sarikaputi, commander of the Royal Thai Marine
Corps (RTMC), and Lieutenant General So Loc of the Third Region
Army in Cambodia's Kompong Som, the Bangkok Post reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The joint operation was a step closer to settling the water
disputes between the two countries, a RTMC source was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The source said the cooperation would enable both countries to
suppress maritime crime such as drug trafficking and piracy more
efficiently.
</P>
<P>
It would also help prevent unauthorized ships from intruding
into each other's waters. 
</P>
