<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine May Delay Closure of Chernobyl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Plans to shut down the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant may be delayed if the funding for building two
new plants is not made available, the Ukrainian cabinet said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government's promise of closing Chernobyl by the
end of 2000 was made under the premise that the Group of Seven and
NATO provide aid for building two new plants, a cabinet statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Aid was also needed to improve the safety of the sarcophagus,
the shield encasing the nuclear reactor and settle social security
concerns once Chernobyl is closed, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
Since the aid was long overdue, the Ukrainian government had to
hinge the closure of the Chernobyl upon the completion of the two
new nuclear plants, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two 1.2 billion-U.S. dollar plants, Khmel'nitskiv and
Rovno, are near completion, but building has stopped because of
shortage of western aid.
</P>
<P>
In April 1986 the No.4 reactor of the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant exploded. Thousands of people are believed to have died as a
result of the worst nuclear accident in history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
