<HEADLINE> U.S. to Feature Star Athletics at Goodwill Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States will send its
best athletes to compete in the track and field events against an
already stellar international group of stars at the Goodwill Games
scheduled for July 19-22 in the New York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. team will be led by Olympic and world champion Michael
Johnson, Dan O'brien and Marion Jones, and according to Mike
Plant, Goodwill Games president, the squad is loaded with
championship talent in every event.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who won the gold medals in both the 200 and 400 meters
at the 1996 Olympics, has decided to run only 400 meters at the
Nassau County's Mitchel athletic complex. The American has been
troubled by a nagging injury this season, and looked not as sharp
as he used to be in the one-lap race.
</P>
<P>
But Jones is expected to shine on the track when she runs 100m
and 200m on July 19 and 20. She has been dominating the sprinting
events along the way winning three gold medals at the
U.S. championships and the title of IAAF Athlete of the Year for
1997.
</P>
<P>
Undoubtedly the greatest heptathlete of all time, Olympic and
world champion Jackie Joyner-Kersee is going to compete in her
last multi-event in her fourth Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
Olympic and world champion Dan O'brien is returning to the
Games to defend his decathlon title, and looking to break his own
world record. He will face intense competition from Tomas Dvorak,
also an American, the world champion last year.
</P>
<P>
The Games' field events will showcase an array of U.S. talent
including the legendary John Godina, who won the golds in both the
men's shot and discus at the U.S. championships last month.
</P>
<P>
Following are some other U.S. men stars:
</P>
<P>
Maurice Greene, world 100 meters champion last year, Dennis
Mitchell, defending and U.S. champion in the 100m, Allen Johnson,
1996 Olympic champion in 110m hurdles, Derrick Adkins, Olympic and
defending champion in the 400m hurdles, Bryan Bronson,
U.S. champion in the 400m hurdles this year, Charles Austin,
Olympic champion in the high jump, Kenny Harrison, Olympic and
defending champion in the triple jumps.
</P>
<P>
The stars in the women's pool include Gail Devers, Olympic 100m
winner, Kim Batten, Olympic silver medalist in the 400m hurdles
and Suzy Hamilton, two-time Olympian.
</P>
<P>
World big names to compete in the Games include Canada's
Donovan Bailey, world men's 100 meters record holder and Olympic
champion, Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tabago, world men's 200
meters champion, Javier Sotomayor of Cuba, men's world high jump
record holder and world champion, Sergey Bubka of Ukarine, world
men's pole vault record holder.
</P>
<P>
The women's super stars include Ana Quirot of Cuba, world 800m
champion, Sabine Braun of Germany, world heptathlon winner, Emma
George of Australia, world pole vault record setter, Deon Hemmings
of Jamaica, world 400m hurdles champion. 
</P>
