<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drainage Helps Save Harvest in Flood Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A record 96,000 sets of drainage
facilities have been in full operation in China's flood-hit areas
to mitigate further losses caused by flooding, according to
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Floods in south China and areas along the Yangtze River have
inundated more than 4.1 million hectares of farmland in 10
provinces since the rainy season set in this year.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that grain yields from about half the farmland
will be reduced by at least 30 percent, and over 15 percent of the
fooded land will produce no harvest, the State Flood-control
Headquarters was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the drainage facilities, water has been pumped from
more than 3.4 million hectares of farmland, over 80 percent of the
total flooded.
</P>
<P>
This will enable farmers to plant late rice on two million
hectares, which can prevent the 14.6 billion yuan (1.7 billion US
dollars) drop expected in the value of the autumn harvest because
of crop failure.
</P>
<P>
Of the 10 provinces suffering serious flooding, east China's
Jiangsu Province has pumped 3.9 billion cubic meters of water from
495,000 hectares by using 42,000 sets of drainage facilities.
</P>
<P>
In central China's Hubei, one of the most affected provinces
along the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze, 4.3 billion
cubic metres of water have been drained from some 940,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, in east China's Anhui Province, late rice is
expected to be planted on 800,000 hectares after effective
drainage operations which should allow farmers to get back to
normal as soon as possible.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
