<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Capital Slump at Increasing Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's capital surface is
slumping at an increasing rate, especially in the north, where
some areas have fallen by 20 centimeters over the last 12 months,
local press Wednesday quoted latest research as saying.
</P>
<P>
The research using the so-called Global Positioning System and
studies conducted by the National Land Affairs Agency indicate
that Mutiara and Kapuk beaches in North Jakarta have sunk by
between 40 and 58 centimeters since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Moving inland, depression in Rawamangun, East Jakarta, is
between 5 and 20 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
In Maruya, West Jakarta, land has fallen between 15 and 30
centimeters, while in the South Jakarta area of Kebayoran it's
gone down between 5 and 11 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
Hasanuddin Abidin of the Bandung Technology Institute told
reporters Tuesday that the extraction of water from below the
city's surface is causing the land to slowly crumble.
</P>
<P>
This phenomenon also causes river currents to shift and allows
sea water to leach further inland, where it can damage building
foundations.
</P>
<P>
If the depression continues, skyscrapers will start to lean and
crack, Abidin said.
</P>
<P>
"But today there is no comprehensive information about the
characteristics or types of land depression in and around
Jakarta," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unearthed Ancient Vases Proved to Have Greater Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- About 200 porcelain vases
unearthed over the past 20 years, from ancient tombs in Guilin, a
tourist city in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, have been
proved to be of great value for archeological research.
</P>
<P>
The blue and white porcelain vases were believed to be produced
in Jingdezhen, a famous porcelain city in Jiangxi Province, east
of Guilin, during the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644). The vases, most of
which are large and free-standing, were used for interior
decoration, according to archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
Famous archeologist Tan Fasheng pointed to the rarity in
discovering so many valuable Ming Dynasty porcelain vases
at a single site.
</P>
<P>
The vases, featuring traditional Chinese painting, not only depict
flowers, mountains and rivers, but also record the lives of local
people, legends and fairy tales, according to Tan.
</P>
<P>
"The vases are listed as the top State cultural relics and now
in safe keeping of the Guilin Museum," said Tan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-State Sector Urged to Help Unemployed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China's fledging non-state
economic sector should accelerate its expansion to help millions
of laid-off workers find jobs, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The non-state-owned sector should participate actively in the
reform of state-owned enterprises, the paper quoted Wang Zhaoguo,
vice-chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), as saying.
</P>
<P>
Non-state-owned firms are encouraged to merge, lease and buy
small and medium-sized state enterprises and assume responsibility
for the employees.
</P>
<P>
Reform of the system has been under way since 1996. It was seen
as a "low-cost expansion" by private entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
On average, 16,500 people enter China's private business sector
daily, 80 percent of them being laid offs from state firms.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 3.5 million laid-off workers either became
self-employed or found jobs with private firms, notes Jing
Shuping, vice-chairman of the CPPCC National Committee, at a
three-day conference of the All China Federation of Industry and
Commerce, which opened in Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The annual number of layoffs in the next three years is
estimated at between 3 and 4 million.
</P>
<P>
China had had 28 million self-employed individuals and 960,000
private enterprises, which employ more than 85 million people, by
the end of 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Helps Easing Flood Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The People's Insurance
(Property) Company of China Ltd (PICC Property) is bracing itself
for major payouts after devastating floods hit east South and
southwest China.
</P>
<P>
The PICC property has made full preparation in funds, materials
and human resources for settling compensation claims while
donating three million yuan (361,000 US dollars) to the flooded
areas, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters of the company, the country's largest property
insurer, has sent 15 working groups to the flooded areas to
supervise claims work.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-June, Jiangxi, Guangdong, Anhui, Hubei, Hunan,
Zhejiang and Sichuan provinces have been hit by serious floods,
which killed more than 800 people and caused over one billion yuan
(120.4 million US dollars) worth of damages to PICC property
insured enterprises.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Jiangmen branch in south China's Guangdong province
has paid more than five million yuan (602,000 US dollars) in
advance compensation. The Nanping Branch in east China's Fujian
province has settled 297 compensation cases, paying out 16.73
million yuan (2 million US dollars) by July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
