<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Urge Solution to Educational Imbalance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A report issued here today urges
that the uneven development of education in different parts of
China be avoided as part of the effort to achieve the country's
goal of modernization.
</P>
<P>
The report, written by educational experts from Beijing Normal
University and the State Council, points to the great gap in
educational levels existing between economically developed coastal
provinces and large cities like Beijing and Shanghai, and
poverty-stricken provinces in central and western China.
</P>
<P>
Though developed regions have greater populations than the
backward areas, their per capita investment in education is much
larger, in some coastal provinces as much as twice that of the
western provinces, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
There are no marked differences in the primary school
enrollment rate, however, the enrollment rate of senior high
school students in the most developed provinces and cities is
sometimes 40 percent higher than in underdeveloped regions.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this imbalance is a result of the uneven
development of the economy. Most remote mountainous provinces
receive little money or benefits from educational taxation,
despite the fact that their governments have invested large sums
in the educational sector.
</P>
<P>
Coastal provinces are traditionally China's commercial,
industrial and agricultural centers, and the first regions to open
to the rest of the world, while the western regions are confined
by deserts, mountains and other restrictive environmental
conditions so that foreign capital seldom arrives.
</P>
<P>
The experts suggest that the economy be enhanced in the
underdeveloped regions to serve as a fundamental engine for
pushing local education, and that the developed regions should
give a helping hand and the central government should work out
more poverty-relief policies.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the report points out that even in some
prosperous coastal provinces priority has not been fully given to
educational development because people there are simply focusing
on creating economic miracles.
</P>
<P>
China has perhaps the longest educational tradition in the
world, largely the legacy of Confucius, but intellectuals were
humiliated during the "Cultural Revolution" in the mid 1960s when
universities stop enrolling students.
</P>
<P>
It was late leader Deng Xiaoping who in the late 1970s
reemphasized the importance of education to the modernization of
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
