<HEADLINE> Beijing to Replace Minivans by Larger Cars in Taxi Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, capital of China, is to
replace 22,000 yellow minivans called by local people as "Miandi"
with larger, less-polluting cars by the end of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The vans was condemned as an 8-percent contributor to the
city's worsening air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Among the city's 22,000 vans, 18,000 have served more than five
years. An official with Beijing Public Transportation
Administration said that the vehicles should not be worked longer
than three years.
</P>
<P>
The first 200 yellow vans appeared in Beijing in 1988, and the
number soared to 30,000 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The upgrading of taxi fleets became a hot issue in Beijing when
the municipal authorities stopped renewing or issuing new
registrations for minivans in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
It is up to the city's 1,000 taxi companies to choose
successors of the minivans between bullet cars (Zhonghua Zidantou)
and Charades (Xiali).
</P>
<P>
There are presently 1,300 Bullet cars which started cruising
Beijing streets in 1996. The air-conditioned cars are priced at
1.2 yuan (0.14 U.S. dollar) per kilometer.
</P>
<P>
Charade is now most popular in Beijing. Rates are 1.6 yuan per
kilometer.
</P>
<P>
The total number of taxis in Beijing will remain 65,000 which
is the most in the country. There are now 600,000 taxis in China,
an increase from 82,000 in 1988.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
