<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Increasing Number of Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- China's urbanization is now
characterized by sharp growth in the number of small and
medium-sized cities in the central and western parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to a senior official at the Chinese Ministry of
Construction, the number of Chinese cities has tripled since 1980,
and now stands at 666. The country's urbanization strategy seeks
to "control the number and scale of large cities and to give
greater emphasis to small and medium-sized cities as well as small
rural towns," he noted, adding that this strategy has begun to pay
off.
</P>
<P>
Of the present 666 cities, 75 are large cities, 399 are small
cities and 192 are medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
The official said that because of nationwide economic
development, the rapid pace of urbanization has improved the
uneven distribution of cities in eastern, central, and western
parts of the country to some degree. The three areas now account
for 44 percent, 37 percent, and 19 percent, respectively, of the
total number of cities.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the autonomous regions of Inner
Mongolia, Xinjiang and Ningxia and the provinces of Hubei,
Qinghai, Shanxi, Anhui, Henan and Jiangxi are undergoing faster
urbanization than other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The official expected faster growth in the number of Chinese
cities in the coming years, saying the figure will reach
800 by the turn of the century, with more than 700 small and
medium-sized ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
