<HEADLINE> U.S Steps Up Military Presence In Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
stepped up its military presence in Latin America after the Cold
War, a Brasilian newspaper reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According the daily "Jornal de Brasil", a coalition of 60
non-government organizations interested in Washington's policy
towards Latin America found that the involvement of U.S. armed
forces with their Central and South American counterparts was
"substantial" and even less transparent than in the Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
The "work group of Latin America" said that during the 1980s,
the United States was directly involved in Central American wars
and gave military assistance to some regimes in a program approved
by the Congress and controlled by the civilian sector of the
U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, the report said, the U.S. government drastically
reduced its financing support, but there were other U.S. Defense
Department programs, which are not revealed in any public
documents.
</P>
<P>
Today, the budget for anti-drug operations by the Pentagon is
three times greater and, in 1997 alone, close to 56,000 U.S. troops
passed through Latin America, most of them in training activities.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that in 1997 some 2,377 military personnel
from Latin American countries were enrolled in military
institutions in the United States to receive training and a
specialized education of international quality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
