<HEADLINE> East China Province Focuses on Roads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Road construction is expected to
dominate infrastructure projects in east China's Zhejiang Province
during the next four years, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been worked out to improve prospects for economic
development in this better-off province and lift poverty in its
isolated rural areas where there are no roads or railroad services.
</P>
<P>
From 1998 through 2002, a total of 61 billion yuan (7.35
billion U.S. dollars) will be channeled for road construction, of
which 35.35 billion yuan (4.26 billion U.S. dollars) will be
invested in expressways, as mapped out on a blueprint by Zhejiang
Provincial Department of Communications.
</P>
<P>
As for this year, an investment of 10.48 billion yuan (1.26
billion U.S. dollars) is expected to be raised, of which, 4.69
billion yuan (565 million US dollars) will go to expressways.
</P>
<P>
The investment plan is in line with the central government's
call to speed up road construction, said the department
officials, adding that in four years of time, a "four-hour highway
communications" within the province is envisioned.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 2002, total length of highways in the province
will reach 39,600 km, of which 1,192 km will be expressways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gap Between Maori and Non-Maori in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Maori Affairs
Ministry issued a report Tuesday, blaming the economic
restructuring, which began in the 1980s in the country, for
creating a "heavy toll on Maoris", though it admitted that the
economic restructuring has brought about improvements to the whole
social and economic conditions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The report, titled "Progress Toward Closing Social and Economic
Gaps Between Maori and Non-Maori," said that the restructuring
devastated Maori employment in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Though the disparities had narrowed by the mid 1990s, Maori
unemployment began to rise again in 1997-1998, it said, adding
that in March this year, it stood at 18.3 percent, about three
times that of non-Maoris.
</P>
<P>
According to 1995 statistics, indigenous Maoris make up 13
percent of New Zealand's total population of 3.64 million.
</P>
<P>
Maori life expectancy has continued to improve and infant
mortality rates fall, the report said. However, for almost every
other health indicator reviewed, including sudden infant death
syndrome, teenage pregnancy, youth suicide, diabetes, strokes,
pneumonia and mental health, gaps have widened between Maori and
non-Maori figures.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Maori sudden infant death syndrome rate at 6.9 per
thousand was five times higher than the non-Maori rate (1.4 per
thousand). Although the life expectancies for Maori females and
males have increased by 17 years and 14 years over a 40-year
period to 73 years and 68 years respectively, they are 79.2 years
for non-Maori females and 73.4 years for non-Maori males, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
In education, the report said that the proportion of Maoris in
early childhood education in 1997 was 40.5 percent compared with
63.5 percent of non-Maoris. Compared with non-Maoris, Maoris are
less likely to attend early childhood education, to stay on to
senior secondary levels or to gain formal qualifications. They are
also less likely to undertake tertiary training.
</P>
<P>
Maori self-employment and household income have increased over
the last decade, it said, but housing has become less affordable
and Maoris are still more reliant on social welfare than
non-Maoris.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, between 1981 and 1996, Maori
self-employment increased from 5.4 percent to 9.9 percent but the
increase in non-Maoris self-employment was greater, so the
disparity widened.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 36.3 percent of Maori households were reliant on
benefits as their main source of income, compared with 14.3
percent of non-Maoris.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Maori health, education, employment and
economic status lag well behind those of non-Maoris, with no sign
of improvement.
</P>
<P>
The release of the report has caused great concern among
high-ranking government officials of New Zealand. Tuesday, a
number of government ministers were at pains to point out that
government initiatives were helping to close the gaps. They issued
statements outlining measures such as Maori employment programs, a
proposed Maori education strategy and the establishment of Maori
development commissions for health, education, employment and
training.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Winston Peters said that it was to the
government's credit that it had ordered the report and it was not
seeking to hide the problems.
</P>
<P>
"Things are being done but it is no use as a government hiding
from reality," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Water Treatment Plant Begins Operations in Shenyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG July 15 (Xinhua) -- A waste water treatment plant with
a daily capacity of 400,000 tons began operations recently in
Shenyang, capital of northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The plant's capacity is the second greatest in China, and is
the city's first large waste water treatment plant, said Liu
Tiecheng, director of the city's environmental protection bureau,
adding that the plant can handle one-third of the city's waste
water, and 200,000 tons of waste water can be retrieved for
industrial use after treatment.
</P>
<P>
The plant's construction cost nearly 600 million yuan (about 75
million U.S.dollars), part of which came from a 70 million franc
French loan.
</P>
<P>
As the largest industrial city in northeast China, Shenyang
suffers serious environmental pollution. To alleviate this
problem, the city will build three more waste water treatment
plants with a total daily capacity of one million tons, and by the
end of the century the city will have all its waste water treated,
Liu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
