<HEADLINE> Russia Continues Dominance in World Youth Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Russia continued its dominance in
the World Youth Games on Tuesday, netting nine more gold medals in
judo, Greco-Roman wrestling and swimming.
</P>
<P>
The hosts also snatched two silvers in fencing and swimming and
one bronze Tuesday, bringing the total number of golds won to 13
and total medals to 16.
</P>
<P>
Poland won two golds in epee fencing and freestyle swimming, in
addition to the one title earned Monday in epee fencing.
</P>
<P>
China took two golds, one by Wu Hanxiong in boys' foil fencing
and the other by Xin Shu in boy's 200-meter backstroke swimming.
</P>
<P>
The former Soviet republic of Georgia got one silver and four
bronzes, making it third place in terms of number of medals
earned.
</P>
<P>
Other countries that won one gold each Tuesday were Armenia in
the 45kg Greco-Roman wrestling, South Africa in breaststroke
swimming, South Korea in butterfly swimming, and Iran in 76kg
Greco-Roman wrestling. Greece won a gold in 83kg Greco-Roman
Wrestling on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the previous four days of matches, one can see that
Greco-Roman wrestling was mainly dominated by European
contestants.
</P>
<P>
Other categories fought Tuesday included volleyball, athletics,
basketball, handball, rhythmic gymnastics and tennis.
</P>
<P>
In the boys' volleyball preliminaries, France beat Germany
3-1. Ukraine defeated Kazakhstan 3-0.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's matches in the girls' volleyball preliminaries all
ended in scores of 3-0 in competitions between (winners first)
Poland-Slovakia, Croatia-France, Italy-Netherlands,
Brazil-Belarus, China-Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Chinese players again displayed their edge in table tennis,
with both the boys and girls teams beat rivals Russia by 5-1.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese boys table tennis team will take on the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea on Wednesday. The girls team is to meet
Chinese Taipei in the finals on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Tournaments in free-style wrestling and artistic gymnastics
will start Wednesday. A "World Youth Orchestra" will throw a
concert on the Red Square. 
</P>
</TEXT>
