<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Alleges Tech Transfer to China, White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott repeated the allegation here Tuesday that satellite
technology was transferred to China, prompting the Senate
Democrats and administration officials to rebuke him for political
motivation.
</P>
<P>
Republican Lott told a press conference that the preliminary
results of a Senate inquiry concluded that China received military
benefits and sensitive technology from satellite exports to that
country.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized the Clinton administration for "wholly
inadequate export controls for satellites" and failure to protect
sensitive U.S. technology. "National security concerns are
regularly downplayed and even ignored," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lott's allegation immediately came under question by Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, who called it "a pretty partisan
report."
</P>
<P>
"I do believe the issue warrants our attention, but it also
warrants objectivity and very thoughtful careful consideration of
the fact," Democratic Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
He complained about "unidentified sources and very questionable
sources. We are going to have to be very careful about the
distinction between allegation and fact."
</P>
<P>
Both the Senate and the House are investigating President
Clinton's decision early this year to grant a waiver to allow
Loral Space and Communications to launch a commercial satellite
aboard a Chinese rocket. The administration and the company have
denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
Senator Bob Kerrey, vice chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, accused Lott of undermining the investigation by
"threatening to compromise our work, by converting the committee
into a partisan effort."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry dismissed Lott's charges as
"not a serious statement by a serious person." "It's partisanship
at its worst," he told a routine daily press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Lott's allegation "struck me a little bit like Alice in
Wonderland time, you know, a verdict first -- sentence first,
verdict afterwards; facts sooner or later forgotten," McCurry
scoffed the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
After 18 hearings on the Hill and full cooperation from the
administration, "Senator Lott today tried to connect a lot of dots
that, frankly, don't connect. And I -- our judgment here is that
that was not a serious statement by a serious person; it was a
political argument made by a politician for political benefit."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, State Department spokesman James Rubin defended the
government satellite export policy, saying, "It's in the national
interest of the United States."
</P>
<P>
Allowing launching of American satellites atop Chinese rockets
would promote U.S. competitiveness, promote openness in China,
advance U.S. China policy of engagement and help reach the goal of
nonproliferation, Rubin told a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said, "By definition, because it was Chinese technology
that created the satellite dispenser, it reflects Chinese
capabilities, and the United States, to my knowledge, has not
added to those capabilities."
</P>
<P>
In the past weeks, officials from the departments of commerce,
defense and state and intelligence organizations were present at
the congressional hearings on this matter. They tried hard to
disprove the lawmaker's worries, but failed to keep politics
outside the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Backs Social Investment Fund for Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday approved
an interest-free credit of 45 million U.S. dollars equivalent to
Honduras for the fourth social investment fund project.
</P>
<P>
This project will continue support for the successful Honduran
Social Investment Fund (FHIS) program, which aims to increase
access among the poor to small-scale social and economic
infrastructure, to develop social assistance programs for
disadvantaged groups and to contribute to the sustainability of
such investments.
</P>
<P>
Since its inception in 1990, the FHIS has channeled over 180
million dollars for priority investments in education, health,
water and sanitation, economic infrastructure, social assistance,
and the environment.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is some 136.5 million dollars.
Co-financing includes: 10 million dollars from the German Credit
Institute for Reconstruction, 50 million dollars from the
Inter-American Development Bank, and some others. The World Bank's
credit will be provided by the International Development
Association, the bank's concessional lending wing for developing
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Agricultural Services in Cote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank approved here
Tuesday an interest-free credit of 50 million U.S. dollars
equivalent in support of the second national agricultural services
support project for Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
This project is the first phase of an 11 year program supported
by the International Development Association (IDA), the World
Bank's concessional lending affiliate, through the World Bank's
new long-term lending instrument, the Adaptable Program Loan.
</P>
<P>
The core objective of the project is to firmly establish
responsive and cost-effective agricultural services, provided by
autonomous agencies which are majority owned and managed by
farmers, through their representative organizations and other
private sector actors.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the World Bank's credit, co-financiers of the
project are the government of Cote d'Ivoire with 88.6 million
dollars, farmers organizations 56.1 million dollars and some
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980715.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Assists Health Service Improvement in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Tuesday approved
a 44.7 million U.S. dollar loan to Indonesia for the fifth health
project to assist the government in improving the health status of
rural and poor population.
</P>
<P>
This project is designed to achieve greater efficiency of
utilization and equity of distribution of health personnel,
increase the skills of health professionals and improve the
quality of health professional practices.
</P>
<P>
Project resources will be directed largely at the provincial
level as the emphasis of the project is on decentralization and
provincial, local and private sector development of human
resources.
</P>
<P>
The total project cost is estimated at 56.2 million dollars.
Apart from the World Bank's loan, the government will contribute
some 11.5 million dollars. 
</P>
