<HEADLINE> U.S. President Urges Y2K Remedies to Be Ready by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton Tuesday
called for urgent action on solution to the 2000 computer problem
Y2K and urged federal agencies and all American businesses to have
their Y2K remedies ready by next March.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the National Academy of Sciences, the president
said, "because the difficulty is as far-flung as the billions of
microchips that run everything from farm equipment to VCRs, this
is not a challenge that is susceptible to a single government
program or an easy fix."
</P>
<P>
He said he has ordered all agencies to have their Y2K remedies
ready by next March. He also noted that many big corporations are
moving swiftly to prepare themselves, but in spite of all this
progress in the business sector just as in the government sector,
there are still gaping holes.
</P>
<P>
"With millions of hours needed to rewrite billions of lines of
code in hundreds of thousands of interdependent organizations,
this is clearly one of the most complex management challenges in
history," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also announced that the United States will
contribute 12 million dollars to support World Bank efforts to
increase awareness of the "millennium bug" in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Since most computer software programs recognize only the last
two digits of a year, the arrival of the year 2000 will cause many
to malfunction unless fixes are in place. Without a fix, these
computers will take Jan. 1, 2000 as the same day a full century
earlier, causing widespread power outages, transportation foul-ups
and telecommunications failures.
</P>
<P>
According to John Koskinen, chairman of the Year 2000
Conversion Council that is overseeing the government's work on the
problem, some of the biggest federal agencies are behind schedule
in fixing the bug, including the departments of defense, health
and human services, energy, education and transportation as well
as the U.S. Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
However, Koskinen said most of the "mission critical" federal
computer systems should be ready by Clinton's target date of next
March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
