<HEADLINE> 30,000 Ethiopians Allegedly Detained in Eritrea's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The office of the Ethiopian
government spokesperson Tuesday accused the Eritrean Government
of detaining about 30,000 Ethiopians in the Red Sea port city of
Assab.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency (ENA), the
spokesperson, quoting eye witnesses, said the detainees are
neither allowed to leave Assab nor work there and that some have
to report every day to Eritrea's governing party, the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front (EPLF).
</P>
<P>
The ENA did not mention the name of the spokesperson who
claimed that two Ethiopian women there have committed suicide
because they were unable to feed their families.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson charged that the Eritrean authorities have
refused to allow families of Ethiopian prisoners to visit them
and they are denied access to the International Committee of Red
Cross (ICRC) and other international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The spokesperson said the Ethiopian government appeals to the
international community to put pressure on the Eritrean
government to allow the ICRC access to these "prisoners" and
their families.
</P>
<P>
An earlier announcement made by the Ethiopian government
spokesperson said that a second group of a thousand Eritreans
left Addis Ababa Sunday under escort for their homeland.
</P>
<P>
These deportees, who Ethiopia says are a threat to national
security, were members of the Eritrean ruling party EPLF,
involving in gathering information, disseminating war propaganda
and raising funds for Eritrea's war effort against Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,045 Eritreans were deported last month.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Eritrea has deported 4,400 Ethiopians since
the outbreak of border conflict in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
