<HEADLINE> Romania Overburdened With Foreign Loans: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) is worrying about the Romanian economy because the deficit
of the balance of payments indicates that Romania has registered
huge loans from foreign lenders that it will fail to sustain
economically.
</P>
<P>
IMF official in Romania John Hill made the statement in an
interview with the daily Romania Libera (Free Romania) issued
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payments in 1997 was 2.6 billion U.S. dollars, 7
percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) and experts predict a
7.8 percent of the GDP for this year, approximately 3.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This sum is large, with foreign investors continuing to leave
the Romanian capital market and the two credit rating operators
Moodie's and ABCE pointing negative fingers at Romania, said John
Hill.
</P>
<P>
He expected the 3.6 budget deficit, adopted by parliament in
1998, to go up, leaving Minister of Finance Daniel Daianu before
the difficult, heroic hurdle to cut budget spending.
</P>
<P>
"Three years of economic backdrop make future negotiations for
a stand-by agreement with the IMF look bleak," John Hill said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
