<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai to Sell Auto Parts Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Hyundai America said it plans
to use the Web to broaden the distribution of its replacement
parts and generate business for its U.S. auto-franchise dealers.
</P>
<P>
While auto makers use their informational Web sites to steer
new-car shoppers to local dealers, Hyundai is the first with plans
to sell parts over the Web to independent repair shops and car
owners.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai, which sells 150 million U.S. dollars worth of
replacement parts annually in North America, said that the
extranet will generate additional revenue for its dealers, who
will handle all parts orders from auto shops and car owners.
</P>
<P>
The system is set to go live around November and will
supplement the CD-ROM catalogs and electronic data interchange
(EDI)-based ordering systems commonly used in the auto-parts
sector. It will link Hyundai's ordering system with a
password-protected Web site where buyers can search and order
parts from a Hyundai catalog.
</P>
<P>
By selling parts on the Web, manufacturers are making an
important turn in their e-commerce strategies, which have been
focused on integrating relationships with suppliers and providing
information for consumers. Their e-commerce initiatives have been
oriented more backward to the supply chain than forward through
the selling chain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
